But if we're going to talk about tools

268
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:21,880
for mood and mental health,

269
00:10:21,880 --> 00:10:26,240
we absolutely can't discard discussions about our biology.

270
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:29,000
That is, we need to make sure that we're taking care

271
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:30,960
of our normal biological function

272
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:33,880
and indeed enhancing the production

273
00:10:33,880 --> 00:10:36,920
of specific neurotransmitters and neuromodulators

274
00:10:36,920 --> 00:10:38,360
that we are optimizing.

275
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:40,240
Yes, I use the word optimizing.

276
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:43,400
The function of our so-called autonomic nervous system,

277
00:10:43,400 --> 00:10:44,840
that aspect of our nervous system

278
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:46,880
that's humming in the background all the time.

279
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:48,160
It's operating unconsciously

280
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:50,720
to regulate our sleep-wake cycles.

281
00:10:50,720 --> 00:10:55,720
It's regulating how well or poorly we react to things.

282
00:10:55,760 --> 00:10:59,120
It's regulating how much dopamine, serotonin,

283
00:10:59,120 --> 00:11:01,160
epinephrine, acetylcholine we're producing.

284
00:11:01,160 --> 00:11:03,280
All of this stuff is humming in the background

285
00:11:03,280 --> 00:11:06,000
and sets the stage for all the conscious work

286
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,080
that we might put to, for instance,

287
00:11:08,080 --> 00:11:11,480
trying to understand what our life narrative is,

288
00:11:11,480 --> 00:11:14,040
what our unconscious mind is doing,

289
00:11:14,040 --> 00:11:15,880
what sorts of defenses am I producing,

290
00:11:15,880 --> 00:11:18,160
all of the sort of high-level and directed work

291
00:11:18,160 --> 00:11:19,960
that we're going to talk about a little bit later

292
00:11:19,960 --> 00:11:23,240
exists on a background of autonomic function,

293
00:11:23,240 --> 00:11:26,880
of neurotransmitter production, of hormone production,

294
00:11:26,880 --> 00:11:28,360
not just testosterone and estrogen,

295
00:11:28,360 --> 00:11:31,440
but things like cortisol, prolactin and on and on.

296
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:33,920
So it's important to understand that if our goal

297
00:11:33,920 --> 00:11:36,320
is to be in the best possible mood

298
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:37,720
given our life circumstances

299
00:11:37,720 --> 00:11:40,520
and to have the best possible mental health

300
00:11:40,520 --> 00:11:41,880
given our life circumstances

301
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:44,240
and to improve our mood and mental health

302
00:11:44,240 --> 00:11:45,680
consistently over time,

303
00:11:45,680 --> 00:11:48,600
that we have to pay attention to what I'm referring to here

304
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:52,720
as the big six or the six pillars of mental health.

305
00:11:52,720 --> 00:11:54,760
And those are, just to list them off,

306
00:11:54,760 --> 00:11:57,040
then I'll go into a little bit more detail,

307
00:11:57,080 --> 00:12:01,720
sleep, sunlight, although I'd like to modify sunlight

308
00:12:01,720 --> 00:12:02,960
because based on some new data

309
00:12:02,960 --> 00:12:04,480
that just came out a couple of weeks ago,

310
00:12:04,480 --> 00:12:08,200
I'd like to now make that second pillar,

311
00:12:08,200 --> 00:12:11,680
not sunlight, but light slash dark.

312
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:13,880
So we could even just think about it as a light,

313
00:12:13,880 --> 00:12:15,360
when and how much light you get.

314
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:19,040
But what you'll soon learn is that how much dark you get

315
00:12:19,040 --> 00:12:20,680
is also extremely important.

316
00:12:20,680 --> 00:12:25,560
So we've got sleep, light, movement is the third,

317
00:12:25,560 --> 00:12:29,320
nutrition, social connection, and stress control.

318
00:12:29,320 --> 00:12:32,000
Now, these are topics that I've spoken about extensively

319
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:34,480
on previous Huberman Lab Podcast episodes.

320
00:12:34,480 --> 00:12:36,240
So I don't want to go into a deep dive

321
00:12:36,240 --> 00:12:38,760
of each of these six pillars right now,

322
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:41,560
but I am going to just give you a few highlights of each.

323
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:43,120
And then of course, we will provide links

324
00:12:43,120 --> 00:12:44,280
in the show note captions

325
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:46,480
for which you can go on the deep dive if you like.

326
00:12:46,480 --> 00:12:47,920
And I also would like to mention that

327
00:12:47,920 --> 00:12:50,560
if you ever have questions about specific protocols

328
00:12:50,560 --> 00:12:52,560
or tools and you're seeking those out

329
00:12:52,560 --> 00:12:55,440
to our previous episodes or specific timestamps

330
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:57,400
of previous episodes of this podcast,

331
00:12:57,400 --> 00:13:00,760
you can go to our newly revamped hubermanlab.com website

332
00:13:00,760 --> 00:13:02,520
and put any topic of interest

333
00:13:02,520 --> 00:13:05,320
or even several topics of interest into the search function.

334
00:13:05,320 --> 00:13:07,760
And it will take you to the very specific timestamps

335
00:13:07,760 --> 00:13:11,800
and other resources that provide information on those topics.

336
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:14,120
So I'm going to go into a few of the key bullet points

337
00:13:14,120 --> 00:13:15,960
about each of the six pillars,

338
00:13:15,960 --> 00:13:18,160
or what I also refer to as the big six

339
00:13:18,160 --> 00:13:20,040
of self-care and mental health.

340
00:13:20,040 --> 00:13:24,680
Again, this is a necessary list, but is not sufficient.

341
00:13:24,680 --> 00:13:29,240
Again, necessary to do these things every 24 hours,

342
00:13:29,240 --> 00:13:31,240
indeed, every 24 hours,

343
00:13:31,240 --> 00:13:33,460
if you want to have the best possible mood

344
00:13:33,460 --> 00:13:37,000
and mental health, but it is not sufficient.

345
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:39,760
That means you still need to do some of the other things

346
00:13:39,760 --> 00:13:41,240
that we're going to talk about

347
00:13:41,240 --> 00:13:43,240
in terms of directed approaches

348
00:13:43,240 --> 00:13:45,200
at improving mood and mental health.

349
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:47,080
If you are to quote unquote,

350
00:13:47,080 --> 00:13:48,800
optimize your mood and mental health,

351
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:50,160
or if you are, let's just say,

352
00:13:50,160 --> 00:13:53,600
trying to constantly improve your mood and mental health.

353
00:13:53,600 --> 00:13:55,160
But these are the necessary,

354
00:13:55,160 --> 00:13:58,680
but not sufficient pillars of mental health.

355
00:13:58,680 --> 00:14:00,520
So under the heading of sleep,

356
00:14:00,520 --> 00:14:01,960
it's safe to say that most people need

357
00:14:01,960 --> 00:14:04,920
between six to eight hours of sleep per night.

358
00:14:04,920 --> 00:14:06,620
Some people can get away with five.

359
00:14:06,620 --> 00:14:08,880
Some people need as much as nine or 10.

360
00:14:08,880 --> 00:14:12,920
Certainly growing kids, babies, teenagers,

361
00:14:12,920 --> 00:14:15,880
and those that are suffering from some sort of illness

362
00:14:15,880 --> 00:14:18,680
are going to need more, as much as nine, 10,

363
00:14:18,680 --> 00:14:20,980
maybe even 12 hours of sleep per night.

364
00:14:20,980 --> 00:14:23,480
However, most people do well to get somewhere

365
00:14:23,480 --> 00:14:25,920
between six and eight hours of sleep per night.

366
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:27,420
You're just going to have to experiment

367
00:14:27,420 --> 00:14:29,800
and figure out what's best for you.

368
00:14:29,800 --> 00:14:30,960
Now, one thing I heard recently,

369
00:14:30,960 --> 00:14:33,320
so I can't claim this as an original idea,

370
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:36,460
but that I think is a really good way to think about sleep,

371
00:14:36,460 --> 00:14:39,220
is that sleep, much like physical fitness,

372
00:14:39,220 --> 00:14:41,920
is something that we have to constantly be working on.

373
00:14:41,920 --> 00:14:42,840
It's not the sort of thing

374
00:14:42,840 --> 00:14:44,560
where you can get a great night's sleep one night,

375
00:14:44,560 --> 00:14:45,600
and then the next night,

376
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:47,480
just kind of let all the protocols go

377
00:14:47,480 --> 00:14:49,400
and expect to get a great night's sleep.

378
00:14:49,400 --> 00:14:50,600
You don't have to be neurotic

379
00:14:50,600 --> 00:14:51,840
about getting a great night's sleep.

380
00:14:51,840 --> 00:14:53,940
Indeed, I do believe that we should strive

381
00:14:53,940 --> 00:14:55,880
to get enough quality sleep

382
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:58,160
as many of the nights of our life as possible,

383
00:14:58,160 --> 00:15:00,320
and if you can't do that, hopefully it's for good reasons,

384
00:15:00,320 --> 00:15:02,840
but of course, things happen in life, raising kids,

385
00:15:02,840 --> 00:15:05,120
you have emergencies, all-nighters to study,

386
00:15:05,120 --> 00:15:07,480
so you can make sure you get that best possible grade

387
00:15:07,480 --> 00:15:08,900
on an exam, et cetera, et cetera,

388
00:15:08,900 --> 00:15:12,060
but we should all strive to get the best quality sleep

389
00:15:12,060 --> 00:15:15,340
that we can, and as much of it, most nights of our lives.

390
00:15:15,340 --> 00:15:17,600
So it's important to look at sleep as a process

391
00:15:17,600 --> 00:15:18,940
that you're going to be working on

392
00:15:18,940 --> 00:15:20,940
for the rest of your life, just like fitness,

393
00:15:20,940 --> 00:15:22,380
and I don't say that to overwhelm you,

394
00:15:22,380 --> 00:15:25,360
I say that so that if on any given night

395
00:15:25,360 --> 00:15:26,600
you get a poor night's sleep,

396
00:15:26,600 --> 00:15:28,100
you don't stress that too much,

397
00:15:28,100 --> 00:15:29,580
you just get right back on the wagon

398
00:15:29,580 --> 00:15:32,180
and you try and get the best possible night's sleep

399
00:15:32,180 --> 00:15:34,820
the next night and the next night and the next night,

400
00:15:34,820 --> 00:15:35,820
much like fitness.

401
00:15:35,820 --> 00:15:37,900
There's no 10-week program

402
00:15:37,900 --> 00:15:41,580
that's going to transform your physical fitness forever,

403
00:15:41,580 --> 00:15:42,980
just like there's no sleep program

404
00:15:42,980 --> 00:15:44,600
that's going to transform your sleep forever.

405
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:47,520
It's a daily or rather, I should say, nightly investment,

406
00:15:47,520 --> 00:15:48,360
although some of the things

407
00:15:48,360 --> 00:15:50,800
that are going to positively impact your sleep

408
00:15:50,800 --> 00:15:52,400
or perhaps damage your sleep

409
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:53,960
are things that you do during the daytime, right?

410
00:15:53,960 --> 00:15:55,880
So avoid that caffeine too late in the day,

411
00:15:55,880 --> 00:15:57,920
get that morning sunlight and on and on,

412
00:15:57,920 --> 00:15:59,200
but view sleep as something

413
00:15:59,200 --> 00:16:01,240
that you're constantly investing in,

414
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:03,660
and it is a critical investment

415
00:16:03,660 --> 00:16:05,280
for your mood and mental health.

416
00:16:05,280 --> 00:16:06,800
The other thing that's not often discussed,

417
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:08,680
and I really haven't talked about terribly much

418
00:16:08,680 --> 00:16:10,360
on this podcast, is the importance

419
00:16:10,360 --> 00:16:13,520
of having a fairly consistent sleep routine.

420
00:16:13,520 --> 00:16:16,320
Now, I realize that not everybody can get to sleep

421
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:17,880
at the exact same time each night

422
00:16:17,880 --> 00:16:20,040
and wake up at the exact same time each morning,

423
00:16:20,040 --> 00:16:22,160
and frankly, that's not practical.

424
00:16:22,160 --> 00:16:23,560
I certainly don't do that.

425
00:16:23,560 --> 00:16:27,440
However, what we know from the circadian health literature

426
00:16:27,440 --> 00:16:29,400
is that everybody should strive,

427
00:16:29,400 --> 00:16:31,000
again, that's strive, nobody's perfect,

428
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:32,080
but strive to get to sleep

429
00:16:32,080 --> 00:16:34,400
at more or less the same time each night

430
00:16:34,400 --> 00:16:37,880
and wake up at more or less the same time each morning.

431
00:16:37,880 --> 00:16:39,600
This turns out to be really important

432
00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:42,080
for regulating mood and mental health,

433
00:16:42,080 --> 00:16:45,480
and indeed for improving your overall levels of sleep,

434
00:16:45,480 --> 00:16:48,040
getting the optimal amounts of slow wave sleep,

435
00:16:48,040 --> 00:16:50,520
aka deep sleep and rapid eye movement sleep.

436
00:16:50,520 --> 00:16:53,000
And what we know is that ideally you're going to get

437
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:56,000
to sleep within plus or minus one hour

438
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:57,280
of your regular sleep time.

439
00:16:57,280 --> 00:16:59,680
So if your regular two bed time is 10 o'clock,

440
00:16:59,680 --> 00:17:01,120
you're used to getting in bed at 10 o'clock

441
00:17:01,120 --> 00:17:03,640
and falling asleep somewhere around 10.30.

442
00:17:03,640 --> 00:17:06,760
Well, then if the next night you fall asleep at 9.30, great.

443
00:17:06,760 --> 00:17:09,080
You're still within the plus or minus one hour.

444
00:17:09,080 --> 00:17:11,520
And if the next night you go to sleep

445
00:17:11,520 --> 00:17:14,640
and you don't fall asleep till 11.30, don't sweat it.

446
00:17:14,640 --> 00:17:17,360
In fact, you're still within that plus or minus one hour.

447
00:17:17,360 --> 00:17:19,680
However, if you start getting into a habit

448
00:17:19,680 --> 00:17:21,920
of going to bed at vastly different times,

449
00:17:21,920 --> 00:17:24,120
deviating more than or less than one hour

450
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:26,320
from your normal to bed time,

451
00:17:26,320 --> 00:17:28,280
well, then you're going to start to run into issues

452
00:17:28,280 --> 00:17:30,080
such as waking up feeling groggy,

453
00:17:30,080 --> 00:17:32,040
even if you got enough sleep.

454
00:17:32,040 --> 00:17:34,000
So even if you slept the full eight hours

455
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:35,000
that you're used to getting,

456
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:37,080
people who go to sleep much later than they normally do

457
00:17:37,080 --> 00:17:38,720
or much earlier than they normally do

458
00:17:38,720 --> 00:17:41,840
start getting into kind of issues of mood regulation,

459
00:17:41,840 --> 00:17:43,640
energy regulation, not just in the morning,

460
00:17:43,640 --> 00:17:44,720
but in the afternoon.

461
00:17:44,720 --> 00:17:47,440
Likewise, try and wake up at more or less the same time

462
00:17:47,440 --> 00:17:49,520
each morning, plus or minus one hour.

463
00:17:49,520 --> 00:17:51,240
That's really going to help you anchor

464
00:17:51,240 --> 00:17:52,800
your overall sleep schedule.

465
00:17:52,800 --> 00:17:56,040
And it's really going to help lead to predictability

466
00:17:56,040 --> 00:17:58,520
of your overall levels of energy, mood

467
00:17:58,520 --> 00:18:00,040
and focus throughout the day.

468
00:18:00,040 --> 00:18:02,880
The second pillar in that big six is light.

469
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:05,480
And I used to refer to this as sunlight, right?

470
00:18:05,480 --> 00:18:07,320
I'd say, and I'm going to say it again now,

471
00:18:07,320 --> 00:18:08,920
although I've covered this in a lot more detail.

472
00:18:08,920 --> 00:18:12,080
So again, just hitting the top contour critical elements,

473
00:18:12,920 --> 00:18:16,040
try to view sunlight, that is with your eyes,

474
00:18:16,040 --> 00:18:19,720
view sunlight as early as possible after waking.

475
00:18:19,720 --> 00:18:21,760
Whenever I say that, the most common question I get is,

476
00:18:21,760 --> 00:18:23,800
what do I do if I wake up before the sun comes out?

477
00:18:23,800 --> 00:18:26,680
Well, unless you have superpowers that I'm not aware of,

478
00:18:26,680 --> 00:18:28,440
you can't make the sun come out any earlier.

479
00:18:28,440 --> 00:18:31,320
So just flip on artificial lights as needed

480
00:18:31,320 --> 00:18:34,520
until the sun comes out and then get outside,

481
00:18:34,560 --> 00:18:37,920
face east in the morning, take off those sunglasses.

482
00:18:37,920 --> 00:18:40,600
It's perfectly safe to look at low solar angle sunlight

483
00:18:40,600 --> 00:18:43,040
without sunglasses, providing you're not driving

484
00:18:43,040 --> 00:18:45,120
into bright light and you crash, this kind of thing.

485
00:18:45,120 --> 00:18:47,840
Get outside, look at the sunlight,

486
00:18:47,840 --> 00:18:50,840
definitely blink to protect your eyes as needed,

487
00:18:50,840 --> 00:18:53,480
but get that sunlight in your eyes early in the day.

488
00:18:53,480 --> 00:18:56,600
This has myriad positive effects on mood focus

489
00:18:56,600 --> 00:18:59,640
and alertness and nighttime sleep later that night.

490
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:02,520
And it does so through a number of well-defined biological

491
00:19:02,520 --> 00:19:04,960
and endocrine hormonal pathways that I've discussed

492
00:19:04,960 --> 00:19:07,280
on many previous podcast episodes.

493
00:19:07,280 --> 00:19:09,920
And you want to do this for about 10 minutes

494
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:13,720
on non-overcast days and as long as 20 or 30 minutes

495
00:19:13,720 --> 00:19:15,240
on overcast days.

496
00:19:15,240 --> 00:19:17,560
And that highlights the second most common question I get,

497
00:19:17,560 --> 00:19:20,120
which is, what do I do if there's no sun where I live?

498
00:19:20,120 --> 00:19:22,040
I live in an area where there's no sunlight.

499
00:19:22,040 --> 00:19:25,640
Look, if you live on planet earth, there's always sunlight.

500
00:19:25,640 --> 00:19:27,000
There might not be very much of it.

501
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:28,840
That might be very overcast where you live.

502
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:30,320
It might seem very dark, but trust me,

503
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:33,080
there's far more photons, light energy coming

504
00:19:33,080 --> 00:19:34,240
through that cloud cover,

505
00:19:34,240 --> 00:19:36,880
even in the darkest mornings of winter,

506
00:19:36,880 --> 00:19:40,800
than there are at night in those dark winters.

507
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:42,880
So get that light in your eyes

508
00:19:42,880 --> 00:19:44,560
and do it as consistently as possible

509
00:19:44,560 --> 00:19:47,040
and also do that in the late afternoon and evening.

510
00:19:47,040 --> 00:19:49,640
That's critical for regulating your circadian clock

511
00:19:49,640 --> 00:19:51,680
for reasons that I've talked about previously,

512
00:19:51,680 --> 00:19:53,360
but I'll get into in a future podcast,

513
00:19:53,360 --> 00:19:55,360
really explaining how those clock oscillators

514
00:19:55,360 --> 00:19:56,640
and mechanisms work.

515
00:19:56,640 --> 00:19:57,920
But just to keep it really simple,

516
00:19:57,920 --> 00:19:59,640
since this is a toolkit episode

517
00:19:59,640 --> 00:20:01,120
for mood and mental health,

518
00:20:01,120 --> 00:20:04,920
your mood and your mental health will benefit tremendously

519
00:20:04,920 --> 00:20:06,880
from getting morning sunlight in your eyes.

520
00:20:06,880 --> 00:20:09,520
Now, if you need to get more light in your eyes,

521
00:20:09,520 --> 00:20:11,680
because indeed there's just not enough sunlight

522
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:14,200
or you don't have the opportunity to get outside

523
00:20:14,200 --> 00:20:17,360
and view sunlight in the morning for whatever reason,

524
00:20:17,360 --> 00:20:20,840
you might invest in getting a bright light source

525
00:20:20,840 --> 00:20:21,680
that you can plug in.

526
00:20:21,680 --> 00:20:24,760
You probably want one that's as bright as 10,000 lux.

527
00:20:24,760 --> 00:20:26,280
So that's pretty bright.

