00:34:51,240 --> 00:34:53,760
The fifth pillar in the big six is social connection.

903
00:34:53,760 --> 00:34:55,120
And we're going to talk a little bit more

904
00:34:55,120 --> 00:34:56,740
about this later in the episode,

905
00:34:56,740 --> 00:34:59,320
but let's just be very brief and specific about this.

906
00:34:59,320 --> 00:35:02,580
We all need to strive to limit the number

907
00:35:02,580 --> 00:35:06,280
of social interactions that we feel tax

908
00:35:06,280 --> 00:35:09,000
or even vex us that cause us stress.

909
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:11,720
This is something that was covered in depth

910
00:35:11,720 --> 00:35:13,540
in the episode with Dr. Lisa Feldman Barrett,

911
00:35:13,540 --> 00:35:15,080
where she talked about the fact

912
00:35:15,080 --> 00:35:16,700
that we don't just have a nervous system

913
00:35:16,700 --> 00:35:19,080
that regulates itself through experience

914
00:35:19,080 --> 00:35:21,760
and through our thoughts and our actions.

915
00:35:21,760 --> 00:35:25,400
We are, as a species, interacting with other nervous systems,

916
00:35:25,400 --> 00:35:27,760
both of our own species, other humans,

917
00:35:27,760 --> 00:35:30,240
as well as non-human species, dogs and cats,

918
00:35:30,240 --> 00:35:32,600
and if you have them, horses and other animals.

919
00:35:32,600 --> 00:35:34,240
So we need to think about our nervous system

920
00:35:34,240 --> 00:35:36,320
as being both regulated from the inside

921
00:35:36,320 --> 00:35:38,760
and through our own actions and choices and thoughts,

922
00:35:38,760 --> 00:35:41,800
but also through interaction with other nervous systems.

923
00:35:41,800 --> 00:35:44,200
And while we don't always have as much control

924
00:35:44,200 --> 00:35:47,600
over which social interactions or work interactions

925
00:35:47,600 --> 00:35:49,280
we have to engage in,

926
00:35:49,280 --> 00:35:52,080
we should really strive to understand

927
00:35:52,080 --> 00:35:54,260
and indeed pay some serious attention

928
00:35:54,260 --> 00:35:57,400
to whether or not certain types of social interactions

929
00:35:57,400 --> 00:36:01,420
are what she referred to as net savings,

930
00:36:01,420 --> 00:36:04,040
neutral or taxing, right?

931
00:36:04,040 --> 00:36:05,680
Certain types of social interactions

932
00:36:05,680 --> 00:36:07,480
with certain people or groups of people

933
00:36:07,480 --> 00:36:08,760
just make us feel taxed.

934
00:36:08,760 --> 00:36:10,520
It makes us feel stressed.

935
00:36:10,520 --> 00:36:13,600
It leads to negative affect.

936
00:36:13,600 --> 00:36:16,720
That is not good feelings or emotions

937
00:36:16,720 --> 00:36:19,520
and often elevated levels of autonomic arousal

938
00:36:19,520 --> 00:36:20,800
that leave us ruminating

939
00:36:20,800 --> 00:36:22,480
and leave us having challenges with sleep.

940
00:36:22,480 --> 00:36:25,680
We really should all strive to limit those interactions

941
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:27,280
to the extent that we can.

942
00:36:27,280 --> 00:36:28,520
On the reverse side of that,

943
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:31,760
as Lisa Feldman Barrett so beautifully pointed out,

944
00:36:31,760 --> 00:36:32,980
we also have the capability

945
00:36:32,980 --> 00:36:34,820
to regulate each other's nervous systems

946
00:36:34,820 --> 00:36:37,080
in ways that produce savings,

947
00:36:37,080 --> 00:36:39,400
that is, that allow us to feel

948
00:36:39,400 --> 00:36:42,040
and indeed cause physiological changes

949
00:36:42,040 --> 00:36:45,360
that make us feel not just happier, not just relaxed,

950
00:36:45,360 --> 00:36:48,840
not just happy because we enjoy interacting with somebody

951
00:36:48,840 --> 00:36:52,500
but we're a group, but that give us a savings,

952
00:36:52,500 --> 00:36:54,360
that give us the kind of resources,

953
00:36:54,360 --> 00:36:56,960
literally metabolic and neurochemical resources

954
00:36:56,960 --> 00:36:58,640
that make us feel more capable

955
00:36:58,640 --> 00:37:00,480
and give us a sense of elevated mood

956
00:37:00,480 --> 00:37:01,580
and improved mental health

957
00:37:01,580 --> 00:37:04,000
when we are not engaging with those people.

958
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:05,760
And this is highly subjective, of course,

959
00:37:05,760 --> 00:37:07,240
but you should be able to distinguish.

960
00:37:07,240 --> 00:37:09,880
In fact, I encourage you to spend a little bit of time,

961
00:37:09,880 --> 00:37:11,520
maybe even just five or 10 minutes,

962
00:37:11,520 --> 00:37:14,160
thinking about who are the individuals and groups

963
00:37:14,160 --> 00:37:17,840
that I interact with that leave me feeling taxed,

964
00:37:17,840 --> 00:37:20,080
that really seem to drain my energy

965
00:37:20,080 --> 00:37:23,040
and have me ruminating and in a not good space

966
00:37:23,040 --> 00:37:25,400
when I leave whatever interaction I had with them.

967
00:37:25,400 --> 00:37:28,160
This could be a real interaction or an online interaction.

968
00:37:28,160 --> 00:37:30,680
Indeed, I did this the other day based on Lisa's suggestion.

969
00:37:30,680 --> 00:37:33,040
I found it to be tremendously useful.

970
00:37:33,040 --> 00:37:35,640
What I did is I decided to,

971
00:37:35,640 --> 00:37:37,400
and by the way, this was happening on a run

972
00:37:37,400 --> 00:37:38,620
where I was thinking,

973
00:37:38,620 --> 00:37:41,600
a lot of my mind is in a conversation with people

974
00:37:41,600 --> 00:37:42,640
that aren't even here.

975
00:37:42,640 --> 00:37:45,600
I was sort of working through a conversation.

976
00:37:45,600 --> 00:37:47,080
I was thinking about what I would say,

977
00:37:47,080 --> 00:37:49,280
what I did say, what they said,

978
00:37:49,280 --> 00:37:52,480
in an interaction that unfortunately was pretty unpleasant.

979
00:37:52,480 --> 00:37:53,800
It wasn't extremely unpleasant,

980
00:37:53,800 --> 00:37:54,800
but it was pretty unpleasant.

981
00:37:54,800 --> 00:37:58,040
And I realized, okay, that is a sort of interaction

982
00:37:58,040 --> 00:37:59,560
that I would like to avoid in the future

983
00:37:59,560 --> 00:38:01,380
because it wasn't happening right then,

984
00:38:01,380 --> 00:38:04,420
but it was carried forward into a portion of my day,

985
00:38:04,420 --> 00:38:07,880
my morning run that for me is normally very pleasurable

986
00:38:07,880 --> 00:38:10,040
and quite sacred to me, actually.

987
00:38:10,040 --> 00:38:11,520
So paying some attention

988
00:38:11,520 --> 00:38:13,960
to how much of your internal dialogue is with yourself

989
00:38:13,960 --> 00:38:16,160
versus with others and how much of that is positive

990
00:38:16,160 --> 00:38:18,440
or negative is extremely beneficial.

991
00:38:18,440 --> 00:38:20,920
And I'm not talking about always just thinking about oneself

992
00:38:20,920 --> 00:38:22,040
and not thinking about others.

993
00:38:22,040 --> 00:38:24,500
To the contrary, we also need to think,

994
00:38:24,500 --> 00:38:26,600
as Lisa pointed out,

995
00:38:26,600 --> 00:38:29,940
about who are the people with whom we interact with

996
00:38:29,940 --> 00:38:34,400
or observe that lead us to have ongoing dialogue with them

997
00:38:34,400 --> 00:38:36,520
in our mind or think about those interactions

998
00:38:36,520 --> 00:38:38,200
in ways that give us energy,

999
00:38:38,200 --> 00:38:40,220
that lead to energetic savings,

1000
00:38:40,220 --> 00:38:42,540
literally metabolic savings that we can apply,

1001
00:38:42,540 --> 00:38:44,580
not just in those interactions,

1002
00:38:44,580 --> 00:38:47,620
but in our work endeavors and our solo endeavors,

1003
00:38:47,620 --> 00:38:48,460
whatever that we're doing

1004
00:38:48,460 --> 00:38:49,880
when we are away from those people.

1005
00:38:49,880 --> 00:38:54,880
So while this concept of savings or neutral or taxation

1006
00:38:56,200 --> 00:38:58,940
of our metabolic and our neurochemical systems

1007
00:38:58,940 --> 00:39:01,380
might seem a little bit squishy, it is not squishy.

1008
00:39:01,380 --> 00:39:03,900
This is a neurobiological concept.

1009
00:39:03,900 --> 00:39:05,620
It's also a psychological concept.

1010
00:39:05,620 --> 00:39:07,760
And it's one that I'm so glad that Lisa brought up

1011
00:39:07,760 --> 00:39:11,800
because social connection, social interaction is so vital

1012
00:39:11,800 --> 00:39:13,400
to our mood and mental health.

1013
00:39:13,400 --> 00:39:15,880
But oftentimes we hear social connection and we think,

1014
00:39:15,880 --> 00:39:17,840
oh, that means we have to spend a lot of time with friends.

1015
00:39:17,840 --> 00:39:19,560
We have to organize dinner parties.

1016
00:39:19,560 --> 00:39:22,680
Well, sure, that's all fine and good if you can do that.

1017
00:39:22,680 --> 00:39:24,720
And I do, of course, encourage people to spend time

1018
00:39:24,720 --> 00:39:25,680
with those that they love,

1019
00:39:25,680 --> 00:39:28,580
but it's also important to take a step back

1020
00:39:28,580 --> 00:39:31,240
and just think a bit, maybe even write out a bit,

1021
00:39:31,240 --> 00:39:33,400
who are the groups and sorts of individuals

1022
00:39:33,400 --> 00:39:34,760
and interactions that really tax you?

1023
00:39:34,760 --> 00:39:36,880
Who are the people that you find kind of neutral?

1024
00:39:36,880 --> 00:39:38,440
And what are the individuals and groups

1025
00:39:38,440 --> 00:39:41,360
that really provide what Lisa referred to as savings?

1026
00:39:41,360 --> 00:39:43,200
That is, they tap into the metabolic

1027
00:39:43,200 --> 00:39:44,880
and neurochemical pathways that lead us

1028
00:39:44,880 --> 00:39:46,840
to have improved mood and mental health,

1029
00:39:46,840 --> 00:39:48,580
not just during those interactions,

1030
00:39:48,580 --> 00:39:50,820
but away from those interactions as well,

1031
00:39:50,820 --> 00:39:54,440
and often pervasively and extremely positively so.

1032
00:39:54,440 --> 00:39:57,020
So this is no small deal.

1033
00:39:57,020 --> 00:40:00,220
This is a really important aspect of our mental health.

1034
00:40:00,220 --> 00:40:04,540
Now, the sixth pillar in the big six is stress control.

1035
00:40:04,540 --> 00:40:07,340
And the reason it's included is that,

1036
00:40:07,340 --> 00:40:09,780
look, stress is going to happen.

1037
00:40:09,780 --> 00:40:12,860
Life is filled with so-called stressors.

1038
00:40:12,860 --> 00:40:15,780
And for a good number of years, in fact, the last 15 years,

1039
00:40:15,780 --> 00:40:18,380
there's been a lot of debate in the field of psychology

1040
00:40:18,380 --> 00:40:19,340
and neuroscience as well,

1041
00:40:19,340 --> 00:40:21,140
whether or not stress is good for us,

1042
00:40:21,140 --> 00:40:22,420
whether or not stress is bad for us,

1043
00:40:22,420 --> 00:40:24,340
whether or not we simply need to reframe stress

1044
00:40:24,340 --> 00:40:25,180
as good or bad.

1045
00:40:25,180 --> 00:40:27,420
And to some extent, all of that is true.

1046
00:40:27,420 --> 00:40:29,780
We know that chronic stress is not good for our memory,

1047
00:40:29,780 --> 00:40:31,580
our immune system, or our health.

1048
00:40:31,580 --> 00:40:34,700
We also know that if you understand the reality,

1049
00:40:34,700 --> 00:40:37,620
which is that stress also allows us to harness our mental

1050
00:40:37,620 --> 00:40:40,700
