01:11:40,220 --> 01:11:41,860
Okay is not an emotion.

1822
01:11:41,860 --> 01:11:43,380
Bad is not an emotion.

1823
01:11:43,380 --> 01:11:45,860
But rather saying, you know, I feel, you know,

1824
01:11:45,860 --> 01:11:47,820
curious but a little anxious,

1825
01:11:47,820 --> 01:11:48,940
if that happens to be the case.

1826
01:11:48,940 --> 01:11:51,900
Or I feel, you know, bored,

1827
01:11:51,900 --> 01:11:55,980
but, you know, also a little bit in positive anticipation

1828
01:11:55,980 --> 01:11:57,420
about what's going to happen tomorrow.

1829
01:11:57,420 --> 01:11:58,240
Things of that sort,

1830
01:11:58,240 --> 01:12:01,560
putting more nuance and specificity on your emotions,

1831
01:12:01,560 --> 01:12:04,200
but also touching into or thinking

1832
01:12:04,200 --> 01:12:07,160
about your own emotional states more times per day,

1833
01:12:07,160 --> 01:12:11,240
clearly has positive outcomes for mood and mental health.

1834
01:12:11,240 --> 01:12:13,440
And the reasons for that are incredibly interesting.

1835
01:12:13,440 --> 01:12:15,760
And this is something everybody should understand.

1836
01:12:15,760 --> 01:12:18,240
Why would it be that putting more specificity

1837
01:12:18,240 --> 01:12:19,280
on what we're feeling?

1838
01:12:19,280 --> 01:12:21,240
So perhaps just in our own heads,

1839
01:12:21,240 --> 01:12:22,720
like thinking, okay, how do I feel right now?

1840
01:12:22,720 --> 01:12:24,720
Like if I were to do that right now,

1841
01:12:24,720 --> 01:12:27,320
I'd say I feel energized

1842
01:12:27,320 --> 01:12:29,320
and happy.

1843
01:12:29,320 --> 01:12:31,120
I do, I really enjoy doing what I'm doing.

1844
01:12:31,120 --> 01:12:35,200
So I wouldn't say I'm like off the charts in awe

1845
01:12:35,200 --> 01:12:38,480
or elation, but I'm very happy and I feel energized.

1846
01:12:38,480 --> 01:12:39,320
You know, earlier today,

1847
01:12:39,320 --> 01:12:41,940
I was feeling a little bit fatigued

1848
01:12:41,940 --> 01:12:43,880
and a little bit confused

1849
01:12:43,880 --> 01:12:45,320
because I was trying to sort out something

1850
01:12:45,320 --> 01:12:47,920
and it wasn't making sense to me.

1851
01:12:47,920 --> 01:12:50,160
So assessments like that,

1852
01:12:50,160 --> 01:12:52,140
which can be told to somebody else

1853
01:12:52,140 --> 01:12:54,140
or that we just hold internally,

1854
01:12:54,140 --> 01:12:55,640
done repeatedly throughout the day,

1855
01:12:55,640 --> 01:12:58,000
anywhere from three to six times throughout the day,

1856
01:12:58,000 --> 01:12:59,840
just periodically pinging ourselves.

1857
01:12:59,840 --> 01:13:00,900
Maybe you set an alarm

1858
01:13:00,900 --> 01:13:03,760
or maybe you just decide to every once in a while,

1859
01:13:03,760 --> 01:13:05,840
maybe every time you go into an elevator

1860
01:13:05,840 --> 01:13:07,160
or every time you go up a flight of stairs,

1861
01:13:07,160 --> 01:13:09,640
you just ask yourself, yeah, how do I feel right now?

1862
01:13:09,640 --> 01:13:11,480
And thinking about that for a moment.

1863
01:13:11,480 --> 01:13:12,840
And you don't have to write it down,

1864
01:13:12,840 --> 01:13:14,320
although I suppose you could.

1865
01:13:14,320 --> 01:13:16,840
What turns out that just that practice

1866
01:13:16,840 --> 01:13:19,840
can really enhance our so-called emotional granularity

1867
01:13:19,840 --> 01:13:23,680
that can enhance our positive emotions and affect.

1868
01:13:23,680 --> 01:13:26,760
And in addition, it provides us a better sensitivity

1869
01:13:26,760 --> 01:13:30,640
to better understand those negative emotions,

1870
01:13:30,640 --> 01:13:32,660
which sounds like it might be a bad thing,

1871
01:13:32,660 --> 01:13:35,560
but those negative emotions have information in them.

1872
01:13:35,560 --> 01:13:37,200
Right, this is one thing that's often lost

1873
01:13:37,200 --> 01:13:40,280
in those broad categorizations of anxious

1874
01:13:40,280 --> 01:13:41,800
or sad or depressed.

1875
01:13:41,800 --> 01:13:42,640
And keep in mind, of course,

1876
01:13:42,640 --> 01:13:44,640
that some people are genuinely clinically depressed

1877
01:13:44,640 --> 01:13:46,360
and that needs to be taken extremely seriously,

1878
01:13:46,360 --> 01:13:49,280
just like some people are genuinely clinically anxious

1879
01:13:49,280 --> 01:13:51,280
and that needs to be taken seriously.

1880
01:13:51,280 --> 01:13:54,560
But most of us, when we throw out the words depressed,

1881
01:13:54,560 --> 01:13:57,360
angry, sad, we're not using enough nuance

1882
01:13:57,360 --> 01:13:59,960
and it doesn't really apply to our internal states

1883
01:13:59,960 --> 01:14:01,480
or the circumstances that we're in.

1884
01:14:01,480 --> 01:14:03,960
And as a consequence, we suffer.

1885
01:14:03,960 --> 01:14:05,920
It's not just about communicating our emotions,

1886
01:14:05,920 --> 01:14:09,800
we suffer because the data say that the more nuance,

1887
01:14:09,800 --> 01:14:12,640
the more emotional granularity that we have,

1888
01:14:12,640 --> 01:14:16,320
the richer is our experience of the positive aspects of life

1889
01:14:16,320 --> 01:14:20,580
and the more effectively we can navigate

1890
01:14:20,580 --> 01:14:23,320
the negative aspects of life, right?

1891
01:14:23,320 --> 01:14:26,100
Again, negative emotions perhaps isn't the best way

1892
01:14:26,100 --> 01:14:28,440
to even describe negative emotions

1893
01:14:28,440 --> 01:14:30,980
because that label negative implies that we should avoid it.

1894
01:14:30,980 --> 01:14:32,540
And in fact, those negative emotions

1895
01:14:32,540 --> 01:14:35,580
provide a lot of information about perhaps

1896
01:14:35,580 --> 01:14:37,620
social interactions that we should seek to avoid

1897
01:14:37,620 --> 01:14:39,980
in the future and so on and so forth.

1898
01:14:39,980 --> 01:14:42,500
Now, one of the most interesting things

1899
01:14:42,500 --> 01:14:45,820
about this whole process of increasing emotional granularity

1900
01:14:45,820 --> 01:14:47,340
and touching in several times per day

1901
01:14:47,340 --> 01:14:50,420
into how we feel, something that's completely zero cost,

1902
01:14:50,420 --> 01:14:52,060
takes just a moment to do,

1903
01:14:52,060 --> 01:14:53,740
that we can get much better at over time.

1904
01:14:53,740 --> 01:14:55,320
That was clearly seen in these studies

1905
01:14:55,320 --> 01:14:56,980
that people get much better at doing this.

1906
01:14:56,980 --> 01:15:00,060
It becomes more facile for them very quickly

1907
01:15:00,060 --> 01:15:02,860
is that it correlates with improvements

1908
01:15:02,860 --> 01:15:05,700
in physiological metrics that relate

1909
01:15:05,700 --> 01:15:08,660
to overall improvements in mood and mental health.

1910
01:15:08,660 --> 01:15:12,180
And the specific physiological metric that I'm referring to

1911
01:15:12,180 --> 01:15:14,420
is so-called vagal tone.

1912
01:15:14,420 --> 01:15:17,380
Some of you have perhaps heard of the vagus nerve.

1913
01:15:17,380 --> 01:15:18,640
It's the 10th cranial nerve.

1914
01:15:18,640 --> 01:15:20,600
It's an extensive peripheral nerve

1915
01:15:20,600 --> 01:15:25,320
that it goes out of the brain at the level of the neck.

1916
01:15:25,320 --> 01:15:27,720
It's one of the cranial nerves that extends

1917
01:15:27,720 --> 01:15:29,800
to essentially all the organs of the body,

1918
01:15:29,800 --> 01:15:32,200
the heart, the lungs, et cetera, but it's a two-way street.

1919
01:15:32,200 --> 01:15:34,100
It's a superhighway of nerves out of the brain

1920
01:15:34,100 --> 01:15:37,360
and into the body, and it's a superhighway of nerves

1921
01:15:37,360 --> 01:15:40,560
back from the bodily organs to the brain.

1922
01:15:40,560 --> 01:15:43,520
And it's involved in regulating a lot of

1923
01:15:43,520 --> 01:15:44,920
so-called autonomic functions.

1924
01:15:44,920 --> 01:15:46,680
So how fast our heart rate is,

1925
01:15:46,680 --> 01:15:49,280
how fast our breathing is, rates of digestion.

1926
01:15:49,280 --> 01:15:52,240
And all of that weaves together to create those things

1927
01:15:52,240 --> 01:15:55,400
that we call affect our internal states.

1928
01:15:55,400 --> 01:15:58,720
So without going into a ton of detail about the vagus nerve,

1929
01:15:58,720 --> 01:16:02,160
there's something that's called cardiac vagal control.

1930
01:16:02,160 --> 01:16:04,660
Cardiac vagal control is the extent to which

1931
01:16:04,660 --> 01:16:07,880
that vagus nerve can impact your heart rate

1932
01:16:07,880 --> 01:16:12,000
and your overall feelings of calm or alertness.

1933
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:14,440
Now, the simple way to think about this

1934
01:16:14,440 --> 01:16:17,840
is more commonly referred to as heart rate variability.

1935
01:16:17,840 --> 01:16:19,920
Heart rate variability is simply the distance

1936
01:16:19,920 --> 01:16:20,900
between your heartbeats,

1937
01:16:20,900 --> 01:16:23,340
or rather the time between your heartbeats,

1938
01:16:23,340 --> 01:16:26,880
which we know if those timings between your heartbeats

1939
01:16:26,880 --> 01:16:28,600
are somewhat variable,

1940
01:16:28,600 --> 01:16:31,940
that is correlated with positive physical

1941
01:16:31,940 --> 01:16:33,880
and mental health outcomes.

1942
01:16:33,880 --> 01:16:36,020
One of the ways that you can increase heart rate variability

1943
01:16:36,020 --> 01:16:39,200
is to get regular cardiovascular exercise,

1944
01:16:39,200 --> 01:16:41,120
as well as doing resistance exercise,

1945
01:16:41,120 --> 01:16:44,320
and no surprise, getting sufficient amounts

1946
01:16:44,320 --> 01:16:46,480
of quality sleep each night is also going to be

1947
01:16:46,480 --> 01:16:49,380
very beneficial for heart rate variability.

1948
01:16:49,380 --> 01:16:51,900
Now, exercise and sleep, of course, are wonderful,

1949
01:16:51,900 --> 01:16:55,100
but it turns out that there's also a very rapid way

1950
01:16:55,100 --> 01:16:57,080
to increase heart rate variability

1951
01:16:57,080 --> 01:17:00,840
by activating the vagal innervation of the heart

1952
01:17:00,840 --> 01:17:03,940
and the way that the heart and some other circuits

1953
01:17:03,940 --> 01:17:06,080
within the so-called brainstem interact.

1954
01:17:06,080 --> 01:17:10,280
And that's through something called respiratory sinus arrhythmia.

1955
01:17:10,280 --> 01:17:14,200
Respiratory sinus arrhythmia can be summarized very simply

1956
01:17:14,200 --> 01:17:19,000
by saying when you inhale, you speed your heart rate up,

1957
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:23,080
and when you exhale, you slow your heart rate down.

1958
01:17:23,080 --> 01:17:25,920
And it's that exhale, slowing your heart rate down

1959
01:17:25,920 --> 01:17:28,280
that's mediated by the vagus nerve.

1960
01:17:28,280 --> 01:17:30,680
Now, there's a more thorough description of that,

1961
01:17:30,680 --> 01:17:33,200
which I'll just give you now, and it's not that lengthy.

1962
01:17:33,200 --> 01:17:34,860
So here's how it goes.

1963
01:17:34,860 --> 01:17:39,840
When you inhale, your diaphragm actually moves down,

1964
01:17:39,840 --> 01:17:43,580
and as a consequence, your heart actually gets a little bigger,

1965
01:17:43,580 --> 01:17:45,120
has a little more space.

1966
01:17:45,120 --> 01:17:46,880
As a consequence, the fluid in your heart

1967
01:17:46,880 --> 01:17:49,600
moves a little more slowly per unit volume,

1968
01:17:49,600 --> 01:17:53,040
and there's a neural signal to speed the heart up.

1969
01:17:53,040 --> 01:17:56,020
Conversely, when you exhale, the diaphragm moves up.

1970
01:17:56,020 --> 01:17:58,280
That means there's a little less space for the heart

1971
01:17:58,280 --> 01:18:00,000
in the general area where it's sitting,

1972
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:01,120
so the heart gets a little bit smaller,

1973
01:18:01,120 --> 01:18:02,080
a little more compact.

1974
01:18:02,080 --> 01:18:03,720
That means that the fluid in your heart

1975
01:18:03,720 --> 01:18:06,760
is moving more quickly through that smaller space,

1976
01:18:06,760 --> 01:18:09,160
and there's a neural signal mediated by the vagus

1977
01:18:09,160 --> 01:18:10,920
to slow the heart down.

1978
01:18:10,920 --> 01:18:12,940
So that's why inhale, speed your heart up,

1979
01:18:12,940 --> 01:18:15,460
and exhales, slow your heart down.

1980
01:18:15,460 --> 01:18:18,200
That is the basis of so-called RSA,

1981
01:18:18,200 --> 01:18:20,840
or respiratory sinus arrhythmia.

1982
01:18:20,840 --> 01:18:23,420
Now, what does any of that have to do

1983
01:18:23,420 --> 01:18:25,400
with the granularity of language

1984
01:18:25,400 --> 01:18:28,040
that we place on our emotions?

1985
01:18:28,040 --> 01:18:30,320
Turns out there's several studies showing

1986
01:18:30,320 --> 01:18:35,080
that when people place more descriptive granularity

1987
01:18:35,080 --> 01:18:37,700
on their emotions, that is correlated with, okay?

1988
01:18:37,700 --> 01:18:41,020
It's not causal, but it's correlated with improvements

1989
01:18:41,020 --> 01:18:43,060
in respiratory sinus arrhythmia,

1990
01:18:43,060 --> 01:18:44,980
which we know correlate with improvements

1991
01:18:44,980 --> 01:18:46,460
in heart rate variability.

1992
01:18:46,460 --> 01:18:48,620
Indeed, it's one of the major bases

1993
01:18:48,620 --> 01:18:50,020
for heart rate variability,

1994
01:18:50,020 --> 01:18:51,620
which we know is correlated

1995
01:18:51,620 --> 01:18:54,780
with not just positive physical health outcomes,

1996
01:18:54,780 --> 01:18:56,820
but positive mental health outcomes,

1997
01:18:56,820 --> 01:18:59,540
including lower levels of anxiety, improved sleep,

1998
01:18:59,540 --> 01:19:01,240
and overall levels of mood.

1999
01:19:01,240 --> 01:19:03,520
This is a topic that I'm very familiar with,

2000
01:19:03,520 --> 01:19:05,620
because last year, my laboratory

2001
01:19:05,620 --> 01:19:07,260
at Stanford University School of Medicine

2002
01:19:07,260 --> 01:19:09,200
in collaboration with a colleague of mine,

2003
01:19:09,200 --> 01:19:12,620
Dr. David Spiegel, our Associate Chair of Psychiatry,

2004
01:19:12,620 --> 01:19:15,020
also at Stanford University School of Medicine,

2005
01:19:15,020 --> 01:19:18,080
published a clinical trial in Cell Reports Medicine,

2006
01:19:18,080 --> 01:19:21,420
showing that there's a particular pattern of breathing

2007
01:19:21,420 --> 01:19:25,120
that people can do for just five minutes per day

2008
01:19:25,120 --> 01:19:28,540
that is effective in significantly improving

2009
01:19:28,540 --> 01:19:33,540
various metrics related to mood, and reducing anxiety,

2010
01:19:33,920 --> 01:19:35,940
and also improving sleep.

2011
01:19:35,940 --> 01:19:38,740
Although I should say the protocol I'm about to describe

2012
01:19:38,740 --> 01:19:42,460
didn't uniformly improve all of those metrics.

2013
