01:22:29,120 --> 01:22:30,380
on our autonomic nervous system

2082
01:22:30,380 --> 01:22:32,380
and slow our heart rate down deliberately

2083
01:22:32,380 --> 01:22:33,380
through our breathing,

2084
01:22:33,380 --> 01:22:36,100
and perhaps even just by stopping and reflecting

2085
01:22:36,100 --> 01:22:38,300
on what our emotional states are

2086
01:22:38,300 --> 01:22:40,860
is really beneficial for our overall mood

2087
01:22:40,860 --> 01:22:41,700
and mental health.

2088
01:22:41,700 --> 01:22:43,340
And I want to highlight, bold,

2089
01:22:43,340 --> 01:22:45,980
and underline that word overall,

2090
01:22:45,980 --> 01:22:47,140
because it's not just the case

2091
01:22:47,140 --> 01:22:49,560
that people experience elevated mood and mental health

2092
01:22:49,560 --> 01:22:50,940
in the moments where they stop and go,

2093
01:22:50,940 --> 01:22:52,140
oh, how am I feeling?

2094
01:22:52,140 --> 01:22:55,980
Oh, you know, am I feeling bored or agitated?

2095
01:22:55,980 --> 01:22:58,180
Do I feel particularly excited?

2096
01:22:58,180 --> 01:23:02,180
Sure, that can have some impact on physiological metrics

2097
01:23:02,180 --> 01:23:03,300
and mood and mental health,

2098
01:23:03,300 --> 01:23:05,260
but in all of these studies,

2099
01:23:05,260 --> 01:23:08,260
the outcome seems to be that people's overall levels

2100
01:23:08,260 --> 01:23:09,960
of mood and mental health are enhanced,

2101
01:23:09,960 --> 01:23:12,100
not just while they're thinking about their emotions

2102
01:23:12,100 --> 01:23:14,700
or doing this five-minute-a-day cyclic sighing,

2103
01:23:14,700 --> 01:23:17,020
but around the clock, which is really terrific

2104
01:23:17,020 --> 01:23:18,920
because I think that's what most all of us want,

2105
01:23:18,920 --> 01:23:20,880
which is improved mood and mental health,

2106
01:23:20,880 --> 01:23:23,380
not just in the moments when we do a practice

2107
01:23:23,380 --> 01:23:24,740
or in the few minutes afterwards,

2108
01:23:24,740 --> 01:23:27,100
but 24 hours a day.

2109
01:23:27,100 --> 01:23:29,140
I suppose we might segment out sleep

2110
01:23:29,140 --> 01:23:31,100
during which, you know, hopefully we're having great dreams

2111
01:23:31,100 --> 01:23:33,120
as opposed to other kinds of dreams.

2112
01:23:33,120 --> 01:23:37,260
But the point is everyone, I have to imagine,

2113
01:23:37,260 --> 01:23:38,620
would like to feel better

2114
01:23:38,620 --> 01:23:40,700
and have elevated mood and mental health

2115
01:23:40,700 --> 01:23:42,140
during the times when they're awake.

2116
01:23:42,140 --> 01:23:44,460
And indeed, these sorts of protocols

2117
01:23:44,460 --> 01:23:45,760
have been shown to do that,

2118
01:23:45,760 --> 01:23:47,860
or so say the scientific data.

2119
01:23:47,860 --> 01:23:49,540
Now we are going to discuss the tools

2120
01:23:49,540 --> 01:23:51,660
for enhancing mood and mental health

2121
01:23:51,660 --> 01:23:53,640
gleaned from the four-episode guest series

2122
01:23:53,640 --> 01:23:55,180
with Dr. Paul Conti,

2123
01:23:55,180 --> 01:23:58,440
who is a medical doctor specializing in psychiatry.

2124
01:23:58,440 --> 01:24:01,240
He also has particular expertise in trauma.

2125
01:24:01,240 --> 01:24:02,860
However, the four-episode guest series

2126
01:24:02,860 --> 01:24:04,360
that we did with Dr. Conti

2127
01:24:04,360 --> 01:24:06,840
was really about exploring the self,

2128
01:24:06,840 --> 01:24:09,160
as well as tools and protocols

2129
01:24:09,160 --> 01:24:12,120
for not just gaining a better understanding of oneself,

2130
01:24:12,120 --> 01:24:14,000
but also for gaining a better understanding

2131
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:18,160
and tools for relating to others, AKA relationships.

2132
01:24:18,160 --> 01:24:20,440
Thread through the series was a model of the mind

2133
01:24:20,440 --> 01:24:22,700
and how it works to create everything

2134
01:24:22,700 --> 01:24:25,660
from feelings, thoughts, to behaviors

2135
01:24:25,660 --> 01:24:28,900
that Dr. Paul Conti described as an iceberg model.

2136
01:24:28,900 --> 01:24:31,000
And I perhaps should refer you to the fact

2137
01:24:31,000 --> 01:24:33,220
that he actually drew out this model

2138
01:24:33,220 --> 01:24:35,760
and we provided it as a zero-cost PDF

2139
01:24:35,760 --> 01:24:36,880
in the show note captions

2140
01:24:36,880 --> 01:24:38,900
for every single one of those episodes

2141
01:24:38,900 --> 01:24:40,740
in that four-episode series.

2142
01:24:40,740 --> 01:24:42,980
We also provide a link to this model

2143
01:24:42,980 --> 01:24:46,060
in the show note captions for this tools episode.

2144
01:24:46,060 --> 01:24:47,860
The model is called the iceberg model.

2145
01:24:47,860 --> 01:24:50,620
And as the name suggests, it resembles an iceberg

2146
01:24:50,620 --> 01:24:54,380
in which the vast majority of our mind's processing

2147
01:24:54,380 --> 01:24:58,080
occurs below our conscious awareness in our unconscious mind.

2148
01:24:58,080 --> 01:24:59,420
So that's the portion of the iceberg

2149
01:24:59,420 --> 01:25:01,360
that resides below the surface.

2150
01:25:01,360 --> 01:25:03,180
Whereas the portion of our mental processing

2151
01:25:03,180 --> 01:25:06,800
that we are aware of resides above the water surface,

2152
01:25:06,800 --> 01:25:08,260
the so-called conscious mind.

2153
01:25:08,260 --> 01:25:10,140
So a key aspect of the iceberg model

2154
01:25:10,140 --> 01:25:12,840
is that the unconscious mind is responsible

2155
01:25:12,840 --> 01:25:15,540
for the vast majority of our feelings,

2156
01:25:15,540 --> 01:25:16,960
thoughts, and behaviors,

2157
01:25:16,960 --> 01:25:18,280
but that we are not aware

2158
01:25:18,280 --> 01:25:20,760
of how this unconscious mind is doing that.

2159
01:25:20,760 --> 01:25:23,160
And by extension, the tools and protocols

2160
01:25:23,160 --> 01:25:24,760
that Dr. Conti described,

2161
01:25:24,760 --> 01:25:27,880
largely deal with going into the unconscious

2162
01:25:27,880 --> 01:25:30,200
and figuring out how the unconscious processing

2163
01:25:30,200 --> 01:25:32,540
is influencing our conscious processing,

2164
01:25:32,540 --> 01:25:34,960
both in healthy and in unhealthy ways.

2165
01:25:34,960 --> 01:25:37,620
And when we say in healthy and unhealthy ways,

2166
01:25:37,620 --> 01:25:40,880
we're largely referring to the presence of defenses.

2167
01:25:40,880 --> 01:25:43,120
So some of you have perhaps heard of defenses before.

2168
01:25:43,120 --> 01:25:45,280
Some defenses can indeed be healthy

2169
01:25:45,280 --> 01:25:46,960
and others are unhealthy.

2170
01:25:46,960 --> 01:25:51,840
There are defenses such as projection, sublimation, denial.

2171
01:25:51,840 --> 01:25:53,680
And during the course of that four episode series,

2172
01:25:53,680 --> 01:25:55,800
Dr. Conti explains how projections

2173
01:25:55,800 --> 01:25:57,040
are not always bad for us.

2174
01:25:57,040 --> 01:26:01,680
Indeed, they can protect us from panic, from severe trauma,

2175
01:26:01,680 --> 01:26:04,180
but they also can create difficulties

2176
01:26:04,180 --> 01:26:06,760
in processing our own understanding of self

2177
01:26:06,760 --> 01:26:08,040
and of our life experiences

2178
01:26:08,040 --> 01:26:10,680
in ways that can actually be damaging to us.

2179
01:26:10,680 --> 01:26:13,380
So a key takeaway from that four episode series

2180
01:26:13,380 --> 01:26:15,520
is to understand and acknowledge

2181
01:26:15,520 --> 01:26:17,600
that your unconscious mind is driving

2182
01:26:17,600 --> 01:26:20,080
much of what you feel, think and do.

2183
01:26:20,080 --> 01:26:23,480
However, by doing structured exploration of the self,

2184
01:26:23,480 --> 01:26:25,320
and we'll talk about how to do that,

2185
01:26:25,320 --> 01:26:27,000
one can gain better understanding

2186
01:26:27,000 --> 01:26:28,840
of how that unconscious processing

2187
01:26:28,840 --> 01:26:32,960
is influencing what you think, feel, believe and do.

2188
01:26:32,960 --> 01:26:36,080
So once you accept the important role of the unconscious mind

2189
01:26:36,080 --> 01:26:37,640
and you make the decision that you want

2190
01:26:37,640 --> 01:26:39,840
to better understand how your unconscious mind

2191
01:26:39,840 --> 01:26:42,200
and conscious mind are in this constant dialogue

2192
01:26:42,200 --> 01:26:45,120
and how you can have that dialogue better serve you,

2193
01:26:45,120 --> 01:26:48,120
there are a series of actionable tools that you can do

2194
01:26:48,120 --> 01:26:51,080
that will allow you to better understand yourself

2195
01:26:51,080 --> 01:26:52,640
and how you relate to others.

2196
01:26:52,640 --> 01:26:54,040
And the first of these tools

2197
01:26:54,040 --> 01:26:57,080
is to really understand your self concept.

2198
01:26:57,080 --> 01:27:00,200
Now, of course, most all of us know our own name.

2199
01:27:00,200 --> 01:27:02,120
Rarely do we ever forget that name.

2200
01:27:02,120 --> 01:27:03,920
We have some concept of where we're from,

2201
01:27:03,920 --> 01:27:07,660
who our parents are, what our present and future goals

2202
01:27:07,660 --> 01:27:09,180
might be, where we've succeeded,

2203
01:27:09,180 --> 01:27:11,620
where we failed in life and on and on.

2204
01:27:11,620 --> 01:27:13,480
But the self concept goes far beyond

2205
01:27:13,480 --> 01:27:17,680
that sort of CV list or our biography of self.

2206
01:27:17,680 --> 01:27:19,920
Indeed, the self concept has a lot to do

2207
01:27:19,920 --> 01:27:23,880
with our self confidence, our feelings of ability,

2208
01:27:23,880 --> 01:27:26,040
both to overcome challenges,

2209
01:27:26,040 --> 01:27:29,000
but also our ability to serve the world that we're in

2210
01:27:29,000 --> 01:27:31,600
and our ability to change ourselves over time.

2211
01:27:31,600 --> 01:27:33,600
Now, of course, the degree to which somebody

2212
01:27:33,600 --> 01:27:36,080
might have confidence or less confidence

2213
01:27:36,080 --> 01:27:37,480
or the degree to which somebody feels

2214
01:27:37,480 --> 01:27:39,880
that they can exert influence on their environment

2215
01:27:39,880 --> 01:27:42,320
and their goals is of course going to vary

2216
01:27:42,320 --> 01:27:44,300
based on their personal history.

2217
01:27:44,300 --> 01:27:48,160
But as Dr. Conti explained, even independent of all that,

2218
01:27:48,160 --> 01:27:51,040
if one puts in some work to better understand

2219
01:27:51,040 --> 01:27:53,920
their self concept, to really get a clear picture

2220
01:27:53,920 --> 01:27:57,800
of one's self, from that one can develop more agency

2221
01:27:57,800 --> 01:28:00,440
with which to pursue one's aspirations

2222
01:28:00,440 --> 01:28:02,000
and to reach their goals.

2223
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:05,840
And the key concept here is one that's particularly powerful

2224
01:28:05,840 --> 01:28:09,660
for both exploring and building up one's concept of self.

2225
01:28:09,660 --> 01:28:11,960
And that's to consciously and deliberately build

2226
01:28:11,960 --> 01:28:13,160
a life narrative.

2227
01:28:13,160 --> 01:28:15,940
Now, a simple way to do this that can be very effective

2228
01:28:15,940 --> 01:28:19,500
is to create a series of folders or documents.

2229
01:28:19,500 --> 01:28:21,240
It could even be a stack of papers.

2230
01:28:21,240 --> 01:28:23,560
I prefer to do this in electronic form.

2231
01:28:23,560 --> 01:28:26,000
And I confess that even before learning about this tool

2232
01:28:26,000 --> 01:28:29,160
from Dr. Conti, I had initiated doing this tool

2233
01:28:29,160 --> 01:28:31,400
starting back in 2015.

2234
01:28:31,400 --> 01:28:34,240
And it's fairly straightforward, but as I mentioned before,

2235
01:28:34,240 --> 01:28:35,640
it can be very powerful.

2236
01:28:35,640 --> 01:28:39,280
And it simply consists of building out separate folders

2237
01:28:39,280 --> 01:28:41,840
or pieces of paper, and this could be done electronically

2238
01:28:41,840 --> 01:28:44,400
or on real world paper with paper and pen

2239
01:28:44,400 --> 01:28:45,480
or paper and pencil.

2240
01:28:45,480 --> 01:28:48,120
And essentially what you do is you're going to divide

2241
01:28:48,120 --> 01:28:51,800
your life history into some regular increments.

2242
01:28:51,800 --> 01:28:54,320
So for me, the way that I did this is I created a folder

2243
01:28:54,320 --> 01:28:57,760
on my laptop that I actually call Lifetime.

2244
01:28:57,760 --> 01:28:59,100
So that's the title of the main folder.

2245
01:28:59,100 --> 01:29:01,480
And then within that folder, I have a series of folders,

2246
01:29:01,480 --> 01:29:04,720
each of which spans a particular phase of my life.

2247
01:29:04,720 --> 01:29:08,080
So zero to five years of age, six to 10 years of age,

2248
01:29:08,080 --> 01:29:11,200
11 to 15 years of age, and so on and so forth.

2249
01:29:11,200 --> 01:29:14,240
Now I'm 48 years old, so I have folders that extend

2250
01:29:14,240 --> 01:29:17,560
to age 50 currently, although I will add folders

2251
01:29:17,560 --> 01:29:19,080
going forward very soon.

2252
01:29:19,080 --> 01:29:21,760
And the idea here is that for each of those folders,

2253
01:29:21,760 --> 01:29:24,080
you're going to place a single word document

2254
01:29:24,080 --> 01:29:25,200
into that folder.

2255
01:29:25,200 --> 01:29:28,760
And then on that word document, you're not going to journal,

2256
01:29:28,760 --> 01:29:31,480
you're not going to do any sort of extensive writing,

2257
01:29:31,480 --> 01:29:35,600
rather you're simply going to put down bullet points

2258
01:29:35,600 --> 01:29:37,740
with titles, it could be one or two sentences,

2259
01:29:37,740 --> 01:29:40,080
but typically it's just a few words describing

2260
01:29:40,080 --> 01:29:42,940
some of the key milestone events that you remember

2261
01:29:42,940 --> 01:29:45,040
from that particular phase of your life.

2262
01:29:45,040 --> 01:29:46,920
So just for sake of example, I'll read off some

2263
01:29:46,920 --> 01:29:49,200
of the things that are included in the folders

2264
01:29:49,200 --> 01:29:51,780
for my particular lifetime narrative.

2265
01:29:51,780 --> 01:29:54,160
But of course, this relates to my lifetime narrative,

2266
01:29:54,160 --> 01:29:56,160
you should of course, put the milestones

2267
01:29:56,160 --> 01:29:58,920
and key bullet points that relate to your lifetime narrative.

2268
01:29:58,920 --> 01:30:00,800
But again, just to give you a sense of the sorts of things

2269
01:30:00,800 --> 01:30:02,720
that made it into this folder,

2270
01:30:02,720 --> 01:30:07,080
in my six years old to 11 year old folder,

2271
01:30:07,080 --> 01:30:09,900
on that document, I put where I was living at that time,

2272
01:30:09,900 --> 01:30:12,140
the city I was living, the school that I went to,

2273
01:30:12,140 --> 01:30:14,660
I put a couple of teachers names,

2274
01:30:14,660 --> 01:30:17,220
teachers that had a particular influence on me,

2275
01:30:17,220 --> 01:30:19,580
a particular summer camp experience,

2276
01:30:19,580 --> 01:30:21,620
that was not a traumatic experience by the way,

2277
01:30:21,620 --> 01:30:23,600
it was a happy experience, but for me,

2278
01:30:23,600 --> 01:30:25,960
it turned out to be a very transformative one.

2279
01:30:25,960 --> 01:30:27,980
And then there were a couple other things in there

2280
01:30:27,980 --> 01:30:31,500
that are just recollections of childhood friends names.

2281
01:30:31,500 --> 01:30:34,180
So seemingly mundane information perhaps,

2282
01:30:34,180 --> 01:30:36,520
but it looks more or less like a biography

2283
01:30:36,520 --> 01:30:38,140
and yet other folders.

2284
01:30:38,140 --> 01:30:42,180
So for instance, the folder that spans from 25

2285
01:30:42,180 --> 01:30:44,940
to 30 years of age is the time that I was

2286
01:30:44,940 --> 01:30:47,140
in graduate school, so it includes a note

2287
01:30:47,140 --> 01:30:49,340
about graduate school, a note about particular hobbies

2288
01:30:49,340 --> 01:30:50,620
that I was interested in,

2289
01:30:50,620 --> 01:30:52,820
in addition to my scientific research at the time,

2290
01:30:52,820 --> 01:30:54,300
a couple of key relationships,

2291
01:30:54,300 --> 01:30:56,540
a couple of key relationship challenges,

2292
01:30:56,540 --> 01:30:58,580
as well as some things that at that time,

2293
01:30:58,580 --> 01:31:00,700
I was processing about prior years,

2294
01:31:00,700 --> 01:31:03,340
in particular my teen years in high school.

2295
01:31:03,340 --> 01:31:05,220
Now, the key thing here is that whatever goes

2296
01:31:05,220 --> 01:31:07,660
into these folders is what's important to you.

2297
01:31:07,660 --> 01:31:10,500
It could be positive events, it could be negative events.

2298
01:31:10,500 --> 01:31:13,440
It could be events that for whatever reason you remember

2299
01:31:13,440 --> 01:31:15,560
and that keep surfacing in your mind

2300
01:31:15,560 --> 01:31:17,620
that you think might be interesting or important

2301
01:31:17,620 --> 01:31:19,580
at some later time or that you're concerned

2302
01:31:19,580 --> 01:31:20,420
you might forget.

2303
01:31:20,420 --> 01:31:22,100
In fact, that might be a really good metric

2304
01:31:22,100 --> 01:31:23,740
for whether or not you include something

2305
01:31:23,740 --> 01:31:24,940
in these folders or not.

2306
01:31:24,940 --> 01:31:26,520
If there's something that you want to make sure

2307
01:31:26,520 --> 01:31:29,900
that you never forget, but that you think you might forget,

2308
01:31:29,900 --> 01:31:32,020
I would encourage you to put it onto that word document

2309
01:31:32,020 --> 01:31:34,020
and put it into that particular folder.

2310
01:31:34,020 --> 01:31:37,780
Again, this isn't about creating a coherent life story.

2311
01:31:37,780 --> 01:31:40,460
This is about creating a series of segments

2312
01:31:40,460 --> 01:31:43,500
of small collections of key life events,

2313
01:31:43,500 --> 01:31:46,260
positive, negative, neutral, inspiring,

2314
01:31:46,260 --> 01:31:48,420
basically anything that was salient for you

2315
01:31:48,420 --> 01:31:49,980
at that particular time.

2316
01:31:49,980 --> 01:31:52,540
And of course, if you want to put reflections

2317
01:31:52,540 --> 01:31:55,020
about those particular events into that word document,

2318
01:31:55,020 --> 01:31:56,380
you're more than welcome to do that.

2319
01:31:56,380 --> 01:32:01,020
But the basis of this self-concept developing exercise

2320
01:32:01,020 --> 01:32:04,340
is just that, it's to develop a historical sense

2321
01:32:04,340 --> 01:32:05,340
of yourself.

2322
01:32:05,340 --> 01:32:07,380
Of course, bringing you up to present day

2323
01:32:07,380 --> 01:32:09,420
where you will continue to add things

2324
01:32:09,420 --> 01:32:12,100
to whatever word document goes into that particular folder

2325
01:32:12,100 --> 01:32:13,900
for the age you happen to be now.

2326
01:32:13,900 --> 01:32:14,740
Now, for some of you,

2327
01:32:14,740 --> 01:32:17,580
this kind of autobiographical bullet pointing

2328
01:32:17,580 --> 01:32:19,020
might seem like it's just that,

2329
01:32:19,020 --> 01:32:21,900
some attempt to build or write an autobiography.

2330
01:32:21,900 --> 01:32:24,100
But it's very important to remember

2331
01:32:24,100 --> 01:32:26,040
that these folders are for you.

2332
01:32:26,040 --> 01:32:28,260
These folders are not about writing a book

2333
01:32:28,260 --> 01:32:29,220
about your life history.

2334
01:32:29,220 --> 01:32:31,660
Although if you decide to do that with these folders

2335
01:32:31,660 --> 01:32:34,580
at some point down the line, that sounds great,

2336
01:32:34,580 --> 01:32:36,540
but that's not the goal here.

2337
01:32:36,540 --> 01:32:39,100
The goal is for you to build a structured,

2338
01:32:39,100 --> 01:32:41,540
narrative representation of events

2339
01:32:41,540 --> 01:32:43,500
that were key in your life.

2340
01:32:43,500 --> 01:32:45,660
And as described in the series with Dr. Conti,

2341
01:32:45,660 --> 01:32:49,100
this goes way beyond just understanding your past.

2342
01:32:49,100 --> 01:32:51,180
This is really about understanding past.

2343
01:32:51,180 --> 01:32:53,260
It's about understanding yourself at present.

2344
01:32:53,260 --> 01:32:55,620
And indeed it threads into your goals

2345
01:32:55,620 --> 01:32:57,580
and aspirations for the future.

2346
01:32:57,580 --> 01:32:59,500
An important thing to understand about this tool

2347
01:32:59,500 --> 01:33:04,060
or protocol is that it also has a incredible ability

2348
01:33:04,060 --> 01:33:08,380
to anchor you in your perception of the passage of time.

2349
01:33:08,380 --> 01:33:10,980
Some of us track the passage of time better than others,

2350
01:33:10,980 --> 01:33:14,220
both within the day and across days and years and so forth.

2351
01:33:14,220 --> 01:33:17,020
But this exercise in particular is very good

2352
01:33:17,020 --> 01:33:20,380
at allowing you to see how much time you devoted

2353
01:33:20,380 --> 01:33:22,540
at a given stage of your life to a given endeavor,

2354
01:33:22,540 --> 01:33:24,500
whether or not you're stuck in patterns

2355
01:33:24,500 --> 01:33:26,220
whereby you're still engaging

2356
01:33:26,220 --> 01:33:27,820
in certain types of things professionally

2357
01:33:27,820 --> 01:33:29,780
or relationship wise,

2358
01:33:29,780 --> 01:33:32,540
or in any other number of different ways

2359
01:33:32,540 --> 01:33:35,100
that have you in a pattern

2360
01:33:35,100 --> 01:33:37,500
that may or may not be serving you well.

2361
01:33:37,500 --> 01:33:39,700
I want to emphasize again that this exercise

2362
01:33:39,700 --> 01:33:41,540
is not about goal setting.

2363
01:33:41,540 --> 01:33:43,660
It's about your ability to build

2364
01:33:43,660 --> 01:33:45,620
a structured narrative pattern

2365
01:33:45,620 --> 01:33:48,100
from which you can look at it

2366
01:33:48,100 --> 01:33:50,820
and then make a determination as to whether or not,

2367
01:33:50,820 --> 01:33:53,820
you feel that you're currently on the right path for you.

2368
01:33:53,820 --> 01:33:56,180
But it's not about projecting forward

2369
01:33:56,180 --> 01:33:57,580
as to what your goals are.

2370
01:33:57,580 --> 01:33:58,740
We'll soon talk about that.

2371
01:33:58,740 --> 01:34:01,060
We'll talk about goals and aspirations in a moment.

2372
01:34:01,060 --> 01:34:03,300
This is really about better understanding

2373
01:34:03,300 --> 01:34:05,980
what led you up to the place that you are now.

2374
01:34:05,980 --> 01:34:08,060
And it really helps you pinpoint the key work

2375
01:34:08,060 --> 01:34:10,860
that you need to do in terms of exploring your unconscious

2376
01:34:10,860 --> 01:34:12,940
and conscious mind using some tools

2377
01:34:12,940 --> 01:34:14,580
that we're going to get into subsequently.

2378
01:34:14,580 --> 01:34:16,020
So there's really no strict rules

2379
01:34:16,020 --> 01:34:18,020
about how to do this exactly,

2380
01:34:18,020 --> 01:34:20,260
except that I do encourage you to make those increments

2381
01:34:20,260 --> 01:34:22,300
across your lifespan manageable.

2382
01:34:22,300 --> 01:34:24,740
I wouldn't suggest doing it one for every year.

2383
01:34:24,740 --> 01:34:27,660
I wouldn't suggest a folder, one for every 10 years.

2384
01:34:27,660 --> 01:34:29,980
I think a three to five year increment

2385
01:34:29,980 --> 01:34:31,340
seemed like a more reasonable

2386
01:34:31,340 --> 01:34:33,060
and tractable way to go about this.

2387
01:34:33,060 --> 01:34:34,700
So that's one of the sorts of tools

2388
01:34:34,700 --> 01:34:36,660
that Dr. Conti referred to

2389
01:34:36,660 --> 01:34:39,460
as to how to build up one's self-concept,

2390
01:34:39,460 --> 01:34:42,140
which directly relates to things such as our confidence,

2391
01:34:42,140 --> 01:34:44,820
our ability to track our own behavior,

2392
01:34:44,820 --> 01:34:46,540
understand some of our motivations,

2393
01:34:46,540 --> 01:34:48,020
both conscious and unconscious.

2394
01:34:48,020 --> 01:34:51,460
But of course, that practice is mainly a conscious exercise.

2395
01:34:51,460 --> 01:34:54,460
It's really not tapping directly into the unconscious

2396
01:34:54,460 --> 01:34:57,060
in any kind of direct way as far as we know.

2397
01:34:57,060 --> 01:34:59,340
Now we can contrast that with the tools and protocols

2398
01:34:59,340 --> 01:35:01,820
that are designed to tap into the unconscious mind.

2399
01:35:01,820 --> 01:35:03,660
And of course, there are a number of different ways

2400
01:35:03,660 --> 01:35:05,260
to do this that were discussed

2401
01:35:05,260 --> 01:35:07,620
in that four episode series with Dr. Conti.

2402
01:35:07,620 --> 01:35:09,820
But one of the most powerful ways to do this

2403
01:35:09,820 --> 01:35:13,540
is by thinking about and indeed sometimes writing about

2404
01:35:13,540 --> 01:35:16,020
or even analyzing one's dreams.

2405
01:35:16,020 --> 01:35:17,660
Now dream analysis is something

2406
01:35:17,660 --> 01:35:19,580
for which you can find a lot of books out there.

2407
01:35:19,580 --> 01:35:20,580
There are a lot of theories.

2408
01:35:20,580 --> 01:35:23,020
There's also a lot of argument that perhaps dream analysis,

2409
01:35:23,020 --> 01:35:24,820
which has roots in Freudian psychology,

2410
01:35:24,820 --> 01:35:28,980
as well as other traditions is perhaps not accurate.

2411
01:35:28,980 --> 01:35:30,300
I don't think we want to consider

2412
01:35:30,300 --> 01:35:32,580
whether or not dream analysis is accurate.

2413
01:35:32,580 --> 01:35:35,020
Rather, I think we should just acknowledge

2414
01:35:35,020 --> 01:35:36,540
that when we are dreaming,

2415
01:35:36,540 --> 01:35:38,260
in particular the dreams that we have

2416
01:35:38,260 --> 01:35:40,220
toward the later part of our night,

2417
01:35:40,220 --> 01:35:41,340
which are the dreams associated

2418
01:35:41,340 --> 01:35:42,940
with rapid eye movement sleep

2419
01:35:42,940 --> 01:35:45,580
that tend to be very emotionally late in dreams

2420
01:35:45,580 --> 01:35:48,620
as compared to the dreams that we have earlier in the night.

2421
01:35:48,620 --> 01:35:51,260
Well, when we consider the content of those dreams,

2422
01:35:51,260 --> 01:35:53,140
even if we're not trying to interpret them,

2423
01:35:53,140 --> 01:35:55,540
it's very clear that those dreams reflect

2424
01:35:55,540 --> 01:35:58,100
the unconscious mind controlling more

2425
01:35:58,100 --> 01:36:00,380
of our internal dialogue

2426
01:36:00,380 --> 01:36:02,660
or what we are experiencing at that time.

2427
01:36:02,660 --> 01:36:03,660
Whereas when we are awake,

2428
01:36:03,660 --> 01:36:06,660
our conscious mind tends to take over more of the narrative,

2429
01:36:06,660 --> 01:36:08,660
the internal narrative and the control

2430
01:36:08,660 --> 01:36:10,260
of our feelings, thoughts and behaviors.

2431
01:36:10,260 --> 01:36:11,260
But as I mentioned before,

2432
01:36:11,260 --> 01:36:14,100
the unconscious mind is always exerting an influence

2433
01:36:14,100 --> 01:36:16,700
regardless of whether or not we are asleep or awake.

2434
01:36:16,740 --> 01:36:19,500
With that said, one way to explore the unconscious mind

2435
01:36:19,500 --> 01:36:21,620
and to begin to get a better understanding

2436
01:36:21,620 --> 01:36:23,060
about how it might be influencing

2437
01:36:23,060 --> 01:36:25,540
our waking states and behaviors

2438
01:36:25,540 --> 01:36:29,660
is to actually record and think about one's dreams.

2439
01:36:29,660 --> 01:36:31,900
Now, of course, some people remember their dreams

2440
01:36:31,900 --> 01:36:34,340
on a regular basis, other people don't.

2441
01:36:34,340 --> 01:36:37,340
Some people actually believe that they don't dream.

2442
01:36:37,340 --> 01:36:39,580
Studies out of sleep laboratories at Stanford,

2443
01:36:39,580 --> 01:36:41,580
University of Pennsylvania, Harvard and elsewhere

2444
01:36:41,580 --> 01:36:44,100
all generally agree that everybody dreams,

2445
01:36:44,100 --> 01:36:46,580
but not everybody remembers their dreams.

2446
01:36:46,580 --> 01:36:50,100
So if you're interested in tapping into an understanding

2447
01:36:50,100 --> 01:36:52,940
of what your dreams are telling you,

2448
01:36:52,940 --> 01:36:55,140
which is basically a way of saying

2449
01:36:55,140 --> 01:36:59,700
what your unconscious mind or dialogue consists of,

2450
01:36:59,700 --> 01:37:02,100
I highly recommend putting a journal.

2451
01:37:02,100 --> 01:37:04,580
So this would be any kind of paper and pen

2452
01:37:04,580 --> 01:37:05,900
or paper and pencil type journal.

2453
01:37:05,900 --> 01:37:09,140
And the idea is this, if you wake up

2454
01:37:09,140 --> 01:37:12,060
and you can remember your dream,

2455
01:37:12,060 --> 01:37:14,860
write down a few key bullet points from that dream.

2456
01:37:14,860 --> 01:37:16,700
If you feel you can write out the dream

2457
01:37:16,700 --> 01:37:19,060
in a very linear narrative, this happened,

2458
01:37:19,060 --> 01:37:20,140
then that happened, then this happened,

2459
01:37:20,140 --> 01:37:20,980
then that happened, great.

2460
01:37:20,980 --> 01:37:23,980
But most people find that their memory of their dream

2461
01:37:23,980 --> 01:37:26,020
is rather fragmentary.

2462
01:37:26,020 --> 01:37:28,940
Other people can't remember their dream,

2463
01:37:28,940 --> 01:37:30,580
or at least they wake up,

2464
01:37:30,580 --> 01:37:32,300
they feel like they were having a dream,

2465
01:37:32,300 --> 01:37:35,460
but they can't remember all of it or key components of it.

2466
01:37:35,460 --> 01:37:38,500
And for that, I suggest that you try keeping your body

2467
01:37:38,500 --> 01:37:41,780
completely still and closing your eyes once again.

2468
01:37:41,780 --> 01:37:43,700
We don't quite understand why this is,

2469
01:37:43,700 --> 01:37:47,380
but when you look at the literature on dream recollection,

2470
01:37:47,380 --> 01:37:51,020
it seems that by keeping one's body completely still

2471
01:37:51,020 --> 01:37:53,980
with eyes closed, we have better access

2472
01:37:53,980 --> 01:37:56,420
to whatever the contents of the dream

2473
01:37:56,420 --> 01:37:58,140
that just occurred were, okay?

2474
01:37:58,140 --> 01:38:00,260
So if you wake up and you can't remember your dreams,

2475
01:38:00,260 --> 01:38:02,740
try lying still for a few minutes

2476
01:38:02,740 --> 01:38:05,660
and keeping your eyes closed and seeing whether or not

2477
01:38:05,660 --> 01:38:08,060
that helps surface the content of that dream.

2478
01:38:08,060 --> 01:38:10,220
Other people find that they get up, they get out of bed,

2479
01:38:10,220 --> 01:38:12,460
and then sometime in the middle of the morning,

2480
01:38:12,460 --> 01:38:13,900
maybe even later in the day,

2481
01:38:13,900 --> 01:38:15,780
the contents of a dream will just come to them.

2482
01:38:15,780 --> 01:38:16,980
Well, if that happens, great.

2483
01:38:16,980 --> 01:38:19,900
I also highly recommend that you have a way to write down

2484
01:38:19,900 --> 01:38:21,900
the contents of that dream.

2485
01:38:21,900 --> 01:38:23,140
Now, what you're looking for

2486
01:38:23,140 --> 01:38:25,300
when you do this sort of tool or protocol,

2487
01:38:25,300 --> 01:38:28,620
I encourage you to be wary of any immediate interpretation

2488
01:38:28,620 --> 01:38:31,380
of, for instance, okay, animals in a dream mean children,

2489
01:38:31,380 --> 01:38:32,980
although they could.

2490
01:38:32,980 --> 01:38:35,420
There's not a lot of science that really supports that

2491
01:38:35,420 --> 01:38:36,700
as a firm statement.

2492
01:38:36,700 --> 01:38:38,900
And of course, there are books out there and podcasts

2493
01:38:38,900 --> 01:38:40,420
and a ton of information

2494
01:38:40,420 --> 01:38:42,060
trying to help you interpret your dreams.

2495
01:38:42,060 --> 01:38:43,460
And while some of that can be fun

2496
01:38:43,460 --> 01:38:45,580
and not all of it is entirely useless,

2497
01:38:45,580 --> 01:38:47,700
the goal here is not to interpret your dreams.

2498
01:38:47,700 --> 01:38:49,680
The goal here is to start recording

2499
01:38:49,680 --> 01:38:51,060
some of the key takeaways,

2500
01:38:51,060 --> 01:38:53,380
maybe even the entire narrative of the dreams

2501
01:38:53,380 --> 01:38:55,620
that you have just prior to waking

2502
01:38:55,620 --> 01:38:57,820
as a way to try and understand some of the themes

2503
01:38:57,820 --> 01:39:02,060
that are occurring and recurring in the dialogue

2504
01:39:02,060 --> 01:39:04,100
that exists within your unconscious mind.

2505
01:39:04,100 --> 01:39:06,220
So a key aspect of this tool is that

2506
01:39:06,220 --> 01:39:08,420
you're not going to take any one dream

2507
01:39:08,420 --> 01:39:11,140
as an enormously informative dream.

2508
01:39:11,140 --> 01:39:14,900
It might be, but more important in this particular tool

2509
01:39:14,900 --> 01:39:17,260
is to write down the themes of a particular dream

2510
01:39:17,260 --> 01:39:19,620
and then see whether or not those particular themes

2511
01:39:19,620 --> 01:39:23,580
resurface again and again across different nights

2512
01:39:23,580 --> 01:39:25,240
or across different dreams.

2513
01:39:25,240 --> 01:39:29,260
The idea here is that things that are repeating thematically

2514
01:39:29,260 --> 01:39:32,860
will show up as different components in different dreams,

2515
01:39:32,860 --> 01:39:35,500
but that by keeping a dream journal,

2516
01:39:35,500 --> 01:39:38,200
you can start to identify some of these patterns

2517
01:39:38,200 --> 01:39:40,940
that are occurring from one dream to the next

2518
01:39:40,940 --> 01:39:43,380
as opposed to having the same dream over and over.

2519
01:39:43,380 --> 01:39:45,660
But the point here is that you can explore the contents

2520
01:39:45,660 --> 01:39:48,140
and the themes, that's really the most important word here,

2521
01:39:48,140 --> 01:39:51,960
the themes of your unconscious mind that is occurring

2522
01:39:51,960 --> 01:39:54,540
if you start thinking about what's recurring

2523
01:39:54,540 --> 01:39:56,440
during your dreams, because dreams are a time

2524
01:39:56,440 --> 01:39:59,600
when your unconscious mind is dominating the narrative

2525
01:39:59,600 --> 01:40:01,280
within your mind and brain.

2526
01:40:01,280 --> 01:40:02,980
Now, for those of you that dream a lot

2527
01:40:02,980 --> 01:40:04,340
and remember your dreams,

2528
01:40:04,340 --> 01:40:06,740
as well as for those of you that do not,

2529
01:40:06,740 --> 01:40:09,960
I would also encourage you to explore the contents

2530
01:40:09,960 --> 01:40:13,820
of your thinking, that is thinking about your thinking

2531
01:40:13,820 --> 01:40:15,600
during so-called liminal states.

2532
01:40:15,600 --> 01:40:17,320
And the liminal state during which this can be

2533
01:40:17,320 --> 01:40:20,160
particularly useful is right upon waking.

2534
01:40:20,160 --> 01:40:21,600
So this is different than thinking about

2535
01:40:21,600 --> 01:40:23,340
what you were dreaming about.

2536
01:40:23,340 --> 01:40:26,760
This is about keeping your eyes closed and body still.

2537
01:40:26,760 --> 01:40:29,000
We do think that that's important for doing this well,

2538
01:40:29,000 --> 01:40:30,340
because once you start moving your body,

2539
01:40:30,340 --> 01:40:31,760
you open your eyes and you start bringing in

2540
01:40:31,760 --> 01:40:33,800
sensory experience for that day,

2541
01:40:33,800 --> 01:40:36,680
your mind dramatically shifts towards conscious processing.

2542
01:40:36,680 --> 01:40:40,280
But in that liminal state between sleeping and awake,

2543
01:40:40,280 --> 01:40:41,960
when you wake up and you're a little sleepy,

2544
01:40:41,960 --> 01:40:43,400
maybe you don't want to get out of bed,

2545
01:40:43,400 --> 01:40:45,880
and this happens to me all too often,

2546
01:40:45,880 --> 01:40:48,220
try closing your eyes and remaining perfectly still

2547
01:40:48,220 --> 01:40:51,360
for maybe one to three minutes, maybe five minutes,

2548
01:40:51,360 --> 01:40:54,360
and just pay attention to where your mind goes.

2549
01:40:54,360 --> 01:40:56,720
Now, you might fall back asleep, be mindful of that,

2550
01:40:56,720 --> 01:40:59,040
depending on what you need to do that morning.

2551
01:40:59,040 --> 01:41:03,080
But a lot of people will find that their mind goes into

2552
01:41:03,080 --> 01:41:05,840
this place that's neither sleep nor awake, right?

2553
01:41:05,840 --> 01:41:08,200
This is a state that very much resembles the state

2554
01:41:08,200 --> 01:41:11,280
people achieve in things like yoga nidra, yoga sleep,

2555
01:41:11,280 --> 01:41:12,680
or in non-sleep deep rest,

2556
01:41:12,680 --> 01:41:15,040
although it tends to be more dominated

2557
01:41:15,040 --> 01:41:18,080
by the unconscious mind, a little bit more sleep-like.

2558
01:41:18,080 --> 01:41:20,840
Now, some people find this practice to be difficult

2559
01:41:20,840 --> 01:41:22,440
because they're the sort of people that wake up

2560
01:41:22,440 --> 01:41:24,700
and they're just immediately ready to go.

2561
01:41:24,700 --> 01:41:26,680
Most people, however, myself included,

2562
01:41:26,680 --> 01:41:28,560
find that when they wake up,

2563
01:41:28,560 --> 01:41:30,200
the mind isn't completely alert yet,

2564
01:41:30,200 --> 01:41:32,000
and you can use that period,

2565
01:41:32,000 --> 01:41:35,560
again, just maybe two or three minutes, maybe five minutes,

2566
01:41:35,560 --> 01:41:39,980
to start to pay attention to the contents of your thinking,

2567
01:41:39,980 --> 01:41:42,760
see whether or not your thinking migrates from

2568
01:41:42,760 --> 01:41:47,760
something related to work or to relationship or to self

2569
01:41:48,320 --> 01:41:49,640
or to something you want to do

2570
01:41:49,640 --> 01:41:53,640
or something that you're anxious about and so on and so on.

2571
01:41:53,640 --> 01:41:55,520
And here too, you'll want to write this down.

2572
01:41:55,520 --> 01:41:57,380
So this is very much like the dream journaling

2573
01:41:57,380 --> 01:41:58,600
we just talked about,

2574
01:41:58,600 --> 01:42:01,400
but it's slightly easier for most people to access,

2575
01:42:01,400 --> 01:42:03,160
especially people who have a hard time

2576
01:42:03,160 --> 01:42:04,960
remembering their dreams.

2577
01:42:04,960 --> 01:42:07,440
And again, it's an opportunity to access

2578
01:42:07,440 --> 01:42:09,920
some of the contents of your unconscious mind,

2579
01:42:09,920 --> 01:42:13,360
to learn to look at and see what's going on

2580
01:42:13,360 --> 01:42:16,360
in your unconscious mind in a way that's very difficult,

2581
01:42:16,360 --> 01:42:18,040
if not impossible to do,

2582
01:42:18,040 --> 01:42:20,280
unless you're working with somebody who's very good

2583
01:42:20,280 --> 01:42:22,360
at accessing the unconscious,

2584
01:42:22,360 --> 01:42:25,120
such as a skilled psychiatrist or psychoanalyst,

2585
01:42:25,120 --> 01:42:28,880
and in that way, allowing you to do introspective work,

2586
01:42:28,880 --> 01:42:32,360
which is not structured in terms of thinking,

2587
01:42:32,360 --> 01:42:33,800
trying to think about like, what do I want?

2588
01:42:33,800 --> 01:42:34,960
What's going on?

2589
01:42:34,960 --> 01:42:35,800
Why did they do that?

2590
01:42:35,800 --> 01:42:36,920
Why did I react that way?

2591
01:42:36,920 --> 01:42:37,760
Nothing like that.

2592
01:42:37,760 --> 01:42:40,240
You're simply observing your mind

2593
01:42:40,240 --> 01:42:43,260
and seeing what's geysering up from the unconscious.

2594
01:42:43,260 --> 01:42:45,660
That is, you're getting a portal

2595
01:42:45,660 --> 01:42:47,660
into that portion of the iceberg

2596
01:42:47,660 --> 01:42:50,440
that resides below the surface of the water.

2597
01:42:50,440 --> 01:42:52,440
The next set of tools for exploring the self,

2598
01:42:52,440 --> 01:42:54,760
self-concept, et cetera,

2599
01:42:54,760 --> 01:42:58,120
from that four episode series with Dr. Conti is journaling.

2600
01:42:58,120 --> 01:42:59,520
I'm going to do an entire episode

2601
01:42:59,520 --> 01:43:01,560
of the Huberman Lab podcast about journaling.

2602
01:43:01,560 --> 01:43:03,400
And there are a lot of different kinds of journaling

2603
01:43:03,400 --> 01:43:05,760
and fortunately, there are a lot of great

2604
01:43:05,760 --> 01:43:07,800
peer-reviewed studies about the power of journaling

2605
01:43:07,800 --> 01:43:09,280
for processing all sorts of things

2606
01:43:09,280 --> 01:43:11,800
like emotional states, trauma, et cetera.

2607
01:43:11,800 --> 01:43:14,240
There are basically two categories of journaling

2608
01:43:14,240 --> 01:43:17,440
that are very useful to carry out on a consistent basis.

2609
01:43:17,440 --> 01:43:19,160
And when I say consistent basis,

2610
01:43:19,160 --> 01:43:20,200
that could mean every day,

2611
01:43:20,200 --> 01:43:21,440
or it could mean three times a week,

2612
01:43:21,440 --> 01:43:23,420
it could even be once a week.

2613
01:43:23,420 --> 01:43:25,320
There are really no hard and fast rules about this,

2614
01:43:25,320 --> 01:43:27,000
but when we think about journaling,

2615
01:43:27,000 --> 01:43:28,880
there are really two main styles of journaling.

2616
01:43:28,880 --> 01:43:30,960
One is going to be free associative journaling.

2617
01:43:30,960 --> 01:43:34,360
Sometimes people talk about this as a data dump, right?

2618
01:43:34,360 --> 01:43:36,600
Typically, people will talk about the data dump

2619
01:43:36,600 --> 01:43:38,120
as the morning notes,

2620
01:43:38,120 --> 01:43:40,360
which is when you wake up in the morning,

2621
01:43:40,360 --> 01:43:41,360
you've got a lot on your mind,

2622
01:43:41,360 --> 01:43:42,600
you can't organize your mind.

2623
01:43:42,600 --> 01:43:45,240
People who have a hard time structuring their thinking

2624
01:43:45,240 --> 01:43:47,580
and behavior often find this very useful,

2625
01:43:47,580 --> 01:43:50,360
which is to take out a journal or a piece of paper.

2626
01:43:50,360 --> 01:43:51,500
Again, this is just for you.

2627
01:43:51,500 --> 01:43:53,220
It's important that you realize

2628
01:43:53,220 --> 01:43:56,640
and really make sure that you're the only person

2629
01:43:56,640 --> 01:43:57,760
that's going to see these notes,

2630
01:43:57,760 --> 01:44:00,000
because a lot of people get into self-monitoring

2631
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:01,280
when they're doing their journaling.

2632
01:44:01,280 --> 01:44:03,200
They're thinking about, well, how's this going to look?

2633
01:44:03,200 --> 01:44:04,180
Is my handwriting okay?

2634
01:44:04,180 --> 01:44:05,140
How's my punctuation?

2635
01:44:05,140 --> 01:44:06,360
What are people going to think?

2636
01:44:06,360 --> 01:44:08,120
Is this going to be a good book or not a good book?

2637
01:44:08,120 --> 01:44:10,680
Listen, none of this journaling that we're referring to

2638
01:44:10,680 --> 01:44:14,120
is about your book or your autobiography.

2639
01:44:14,120 --> 01:44:16,200
This is really just for you.

2640
01:44:16,200 --> 01:44:17,840
This is an exploration of yourself

2641
01:44:17,840 --> 01:44:20,600
that's designed to help you enhance your concept,

2642
01:44:20,600 --> 01:44:22,880
that is your understanding of self,

2643
01:44:22,880 --> 01:44:26,240
and indeed translates to better confidence,

2644
01:44:26,240 --> 01:44:28,320
better understanding of your goals and aspirations,

2645
01:44:28,320 --> 01:44:30,800
better understanding of your unhealthy patterns

2646
01:44:30,800 --> 01:44:32,560
and defenses and on and on.

2647
01:44:32,560 --> 01:44:35,280
And so again, the two styles of journaling

2648
01:44:35,280 --> 01:44:36,560
are free association.

2649
01:44:36,560 --> 01:44:38,080
So where you literally just write down

2650
01:44:38,080 --> 01:44:39,840
anything that comes to mind

2651
01:44:39,840 --> 01:44:41,360
or that you feel like writing down

2652
01:44:41,360 --> 01:44:42,680
within a given period of time.

2653
01:44:42,680 --> 01:44:46,220
For most people, 10 minutes is ample time to do that.

2654
01:44:46,220 --> 01:44:47,700
For some people, five will be enough.

2655
01:44:47,700 --> 01:44:51,080
And for some who have the time, maybe 30 minutes.

2656
01:44:51,080 --> 01:44:53,640
But for me, and I think for most people out there,

2657
01:44:53,640 --> 01:44:55,360
anywhere from five to 10 minutes

2658
01:44:55,360 --> 01:44:57,600
of this data dump free association,

2659
01:44:57,600 --> 01:44:59,240
it could be your anxieties, what you're thinking about,

2660
01:44:59,240 --> 01:45:00,240
what you're anxious about.

2661
01:45:00,240 --> 01:45:03,200
Really could be about anything that comes to mind.

2662
01:45:03,200 --> 01:45:06,720
And this free association process can be very useful

2663
01:45:06,720 --> 01:45:09,680
for clearing out the clutter, so to speak.

2664
01:45:09,680 --> 01:45:12,400
The other style of journaling that's equally useful,

2665
01:45:12,400 --> 01:45:15,720
but for different reasons, is structured journaling

2666
01:45:15,720 --> 01:45:19,420
to have a goal for a given entry on a given day.

2667
01:45:19,420 --> 01:45:20,680
And again, this could be done in the morning,

2668
01:45:20,680 --> 01:45:22,000
afternoon or night.

2669
01:45:22,000 --> 01:45:25,440
And the idea would be that you would set an intention,

2670
01:45:25,440 --> 01:45:27,960
and by intention, I mean a specific topic

2671
01:45:27,960 --> 01:45:30,120
that you're going to restrict your writing to.

2672
01:45:30,120 --> 01:45:32,560
And that writing should be about self,

2673
01:45:32,560 --> 01:45:35,420
in particular goals and aspirations.

2674
01:45:35,420 --> 01:45:38,440
What you've wanted in the past, yes,

2675
01:45:38,440 --> 01:45:40,880
but also what you want at present,

2676
01:45:40,880 --> 01:45:43,600
what you might want in the future for yourself.

2677
01:45:43,600 --> 01:45:45,880
These could of course be material things,

2678
01:45:45,880 --> 01:45:49,320
but in general, this is more about aspirations

2679
01:45:49,320 --> 01:45:52,580
of things that you would like to accomplish or generate.

2680
01:45:52,580 --> 01:45:54,160
And the key word there is generate.

2681
01:45:54,160 --> 01:45:56,120
And if you listen to the four episode series

2682
01:45:56,120 --> 01:46:00,080
with Dr. Conti, he talked about three drives

2683
01:46:00,080 --> 01:46:01,480
that exist in all of us.

2684
01:46:01,480 --> 01:46:04,240
These three drives are the aggressive drive,

2685
01:46:04,240 --> 01:46:07,200
the pleasure drive and the generative drive.

2686
01:46:07,200 --> 01:46:08,960
And we don't need to go into a lengthy description

2687
01:46:08,960 --> 01:46:10,360
about these drives right now.

2688
01:46:10,360 --> 01:46:13,260
If you're curious about them and what they represent

2689
01:46:13,260 --> 01:46:16,280
and how they can be in balance or out of balance

2690
01:46:16,280 --> 01:46:18,200
and how that serves us or doesn't serve us,

2691
01:46:18,200 --> 01:46:19,960
please check out that four episode series

2692
01:46:19,960 --> 01:46:21,840
with Dr. Conti, because he goes into that

2693
01:46:21,840 --> 01:46:26,120
in a fair amount of detail and also in an actionable way.

2694
01:46:26,120 --> 01:46:29,120
But the key thing here is that we're generative.

2695
01:46:29,120 --> 01:46:31,520
One of the things that I asked Dr. Conti at the outset

2696
01:46:31,520 --> 01:46:34,360
and throughout the entire series was,

2697
01:46:34,360 --> 01:46:36,160
what is mental health?

2698
01:46:36,160 --> 01:46:38,400
We talk about physical health and we have some idea

2699
01:46:38,400 --> 01:46:40,800
of what that represents, healthy blood pressure,

2700
01:46:40,800 --> 01:46:43,120
the ability to do certain forms of physical movement,

2701
01:46:43,120 --> 01:46:44,760
cognitive abilities.

2702
01:46:44,760 --> 01:46:47,480
I asked him, how can we define mental health?

2703
01:46:47,480 --> 01:46:50,200
And his answer was very straightforward and very powerful.

2704
01:46:50,200 --> 01:46:54,600
He said, what we all need to aspire to is to be in states,

2705
01:46:54,600 --> 01:46:58,800
that is in the verb actions of agency and gratitude

2706
01:46:58,800 --> 01:47:01,480
for as much of our waking life as possible.

2707
01:47:01,480 --> 01:47:02,560
Now that sounds great, right?

2708
01:47:02,560 --> 01:47:04,840
A sense of agency, the ability to exert influence

2709
01:47:04,840 --> 01:47:07,960
over our internal state and affect the world around us

2710
01:47:07,960 --> 01:47:09,880
in positive ways, positive relationships,

2711
01:47:09,880 --> 01:47:11,880
reach our goals, as well as gratitude,

2712
01:47:11,880 --> 01:47:13,320
being grateful for the opportunities

2713
01:47:13,320 --> 01:47:15,560
that we've been afforded, even grateful perhaps

2714
01:47:15,560 --> 01:47:17,320
for some of the challenges that we've been afforded

2715
01:47:17,320 --> 01:47:19,400
or that were selected for us

2716
01:47:19,400 --> 01:47:21,440
that we had no control over

2717
01:47:21,440 --> 01:47:24,440
and carrying that agency and gratitude forward

2718
01:47:24,440 --> 01:47:26,680
because it gives rise to a sense of peace,

2719
01:47:26,680 --> 01:47:28,280
contentment and delight.

2720
01:47:28,280 --> 01:47:30,440
So all of that sounds wonderful, right?

2721
01:47:30,440 --> 01:47:33,120
Be in agency and gratitude as a verb states,

2722
01:47:33,120 --> 01:47:35,440
experience peace, contentment and delight.

2723
01:47:35,440 --> 01:47:36,760
But Dr. Conti acknowledged,

2724
01:47:36,760 --> 01:47:39,200
and we spent a good amount of time discussing the fact

2725
01:47:39,200 --> 01:47:41,760
that doesn't happen just because we decide we want to.

2726
01:47:41,760 --> 01:47:44,480
In fact, agency and gratitude,

2727
01:47:44,480 --> 01:47:46,040
peace, contentment and delight,

2728
01:47:46,040 --> 01:47:48,720
guys are up from a whole set of other processes

2729
01:47:48,720 --> 01:47:51,560
that we have to engage in on a regular basis.

2730
01:47:51,560 --> 01:47:54,520
And that really gets us back to those three drives.

2731
01:47:54,520 --> 01:47:56,440
He talked about how people tend to have

2732
01:47:56,440 --> 01:47:58,200
more or less aggressive drive,

2733
01:47:58,200 --> 01:48:00,560
not just aggression in terms of violence,

2734
01:48:00,560 --> 01:48:02,000
although some people do have that,

2735
01:48:02,000 --> 01:48:03,880
but in terms of their determination

2736
01:48:03,880 --> 01:48:06,320
and their sort of leaning into friction,

2737
01:48:06,320 --> 01:48:07,760
even seeking out a friction.

2738
01:48:07,760 --> 01:48:09,400
People are on a continuum

2739
01:48:09,400 --> 01:48:11,000
with respect to the aggressive drive.

2740
01:48:11,000 --> 01:48:12,800
He also talked about the pleasure drive

2741
01:48:12,800 --> 01:48:14,600
and the fact that people are on a continuum

2742
01:48:14,640 --> 01:48:18,920
of the desire for pleasure to either be a hedonist

2743
01:48:18,920 --> 01:48:21,040
or somebody who really avoids pleasure

2744
01:48:21,040 --> 01:48:22,920
and kind of restricts pleasure from oneself.

2745
01:48:22,920 --> 01:48:25,240
And again, that these things can slide around

2746
01:48:25,240 --> 01:48:27,960
depending on our life circumstances, our age, et cetera,

2747
01:48:27,960 --> 01:48:31,960
but that it's very important that we have a sense

2748
01:48:31,960 --> 01:48:35,160
of where we are on that continuum of an aggressive drive

2749
01:48:35,160 --> 01:48:36,640
and a pleasure drive.

2750
01:48:36,640 --> 01:48:39,920
And here's the most important thing,

2751
01:48:39,920 --> 01:48:42,120
that our aggressive drive and pleasure drive

2752
01:48:42,120 --> 01:48:45,440
never outsize our generative drive.

2753
01:48:45,440 --> 01:48:47,680
And that engaging our generative drive

2754
01:48:47,680 --> 01:48:49,640
is really the hallmark of mental health

2755
01:48:49,640 --> 01:48:52,720
that leads to that sense of agency and gratitude,

2756
01:48:52,720 --> 01:48:54,320
peace, contentment and delight.

2757
01:48:54,320 --> 01:48:57,720
And he defined the generative drive in the following way.

2758
01:48:57,720 --> 01:49:00,240
He said, the generative drive is our desire to create,

2759
01:49:00,240 --> 01:49:02,880
build and contribute to the world in meaningful ways

2760
01:49:02,880 --> 01:49:05,440
and appreciate the process to get there.

2761
01:49:05,440 --> 01:49:08,320
It is the core feature of our mental health.

2762
01:49:08,320 --> 01:49:10,160
So if you want to learn more about the various drives

2763
01:49:10,160 --> 01:49:11,880
and how they interact and how to access

2764
01:49:11,880 --> 01:49:14,880
more generative drive, again, that's all contained

2765
01:49:14,880 --> 01:49:17,120
in the four episode series with Dr. Conti,

2766
01:49:17,120 --> 01:49:19,800
but taking us back to the tools and takeaways

2767
01:49:19,800 --> 01:49:21,600
from that four episode series,

2768
01:49:21,600 --> 01:49:24,400
the process of journaling in free association mode

2769
01:49:24,400 --> 01:49:28,280
or the process of journaling in a conscious structured way

2770
01:49:28,280 --> 01:49:31,760
is really about trying to access the generative drive

2771
01:49:31,760 --> 01:49:34,480
and to build up that generative drive.

2772
01:49:34,480 --> 01:49:37,200
And one of the key things about conscious journaling

2773
01:49:37,200 --> 01:49:39,280
is that it affords us the opportunity

2774
01:49:39,280 --> 01:49:42,800
in a way that's not going to be seen by anybody else

2775
01:49:42,800 --> 01:49:46,040
to really think about what our goals and aspirations are.

2776
01:49:46,040 --> 01:49:47,320
Now you might say, you know,

2777
01:49:47,320 --> 01:49:49,320
I can't even think about my goals and aspirations.

2778
01:49:49,320 --> 01:49:50,800
I don't know what I want.

2779
01:49:50,800 --> 01:49:51,640
Well, that's fine.

2780
01:49:51,640 --> 01:49:53,000
Then you should journal about that.

2781
01:49:53,000 --> 01:49:56,720
However, most people have some sense of what they would like,

2782
01:49:56,720 --> 01:49:59,640
but most people are simply not comfortable

2783
01:49:59,640 --> 01:50:02,920
with writing those things out or even thinking about them.

2784
01:50:02,920 --> 01:50:05,240
And if you reflect on that, how could it ever be

2785
01:50:05,240 --> 01:50:07,640
that you would achieve those goals and aspirations

2786
01:50:07,640 --> 01:50:10,280
if you're not even feeling comfortable enough

2787
01:50:10,280 --> 01:50:12,640
to think about them or write about them?

2788
01:50:12,640 --> 01:50:14,680
And so the process of thinking about

2789
01:50:14,680 --> 01:50:17,360
and writing about your goals and aspirations

2790
01:50:17,360 --> 01:50:20,320
is perhaps one of the key first steps

2791
01:50:20,320 --> 01:50:23,880
towards being able to actualize those goals and aspirations.

2792
01:50:23,880 --> 01:50:26,280
And for some people, this might be very easy to do.

2793
01:50:26,280 --> 01:50:27,320
You can simply write down, say,

2794
01:50:27,320 --> 01:50:29,240
I want to be married by this age,

2795
01:50:29,240 --> 01:50:31,000
and I want to make X amount of money,

2796
01:50:31,000 --> 01:50:32,480
and I want to live here or there.

2797
01:50:32,480 --> 01:50:35,200
And certainly those sorts of goals and aspirations

2798
01:50:35,200 --> 01:50:37,600
are perfectly valid for this type of exercise,

2799
01:50:38,600 --> 01:50:40,040
but so are the sorts of goals and aspirations

2800
01:50:40,040 --> 01:50:41,720
that relate to feeling states.

2801
01:50:41,720 --> 01:50:44,360
Like, yeah, I would like to feel part of a community.

2802
01:50:44,360 --> 01:50:47,120
I would like to feel like an active contributor

2803
01:50:47,120 --> 01:50:48,200
to a community.

2804
01:50:48,200 --> 01:50:50,240
And then the essential thing is to really flesh out

2805
01:50:50,240 --> 01:50:52,720
the detail around those goals and aspirations.

2806
01:50:52,720 --> 01:50:54,160
You know, what size community?

2807
01:50:54,160 --> 01:50:56,560
Where do you see yourself fitting into this community?

2808
01:50:56,560 --> 01:50:59,280
Are you doing this alongside other people or by yourself?

2809
01:50:59,280 --> 01:51:02,040
In other words, to really get comfortable thinking

2810
01:51:02,040 --> 01:51:03,960
about what your goals and aspirations are,

2811
01:51:03,960 --> 01:51:07,080
again, completely from the perspective of self

2812
01:51:07,080 --> 01:51:09,080
and that you are going to be the only person

2813
01:51:09,080 --> 01:51:11,200
to see this particular document.

2814
01:51:11,200 --> 01:51:12,640
Now, I will be the first to admit

2815
01:51:12,640 --> 01:51:15,160
that the exercise that I just described,

2816
01:51:15,160 --> 01:51:16,960
not the free association journaling,

2817
01:51:16,960 --> 01:51:20,200
but the structured journaling of goals and aspirations,

2818
01:51:20,200 --> 01:51:24,080
I and many people find to be difficult to initiate.

2819
01:51:24,080 --> 01:51:25,880
Difficult to initiate because there seems to be

2820
01:51:25,880 --> 01:51:29,000
a bit of internal anxiety and friction around doing it.

2821
01:51:29,000 --> 01:51:32,120
There seems to be something that keeps many, not all,

2822
01:51:32,120 --> 01:51:36,160
but many people from feeling as if they are even allowed

2823
01:51:36,160 --> 01:51:38,120
to think about their goals and aspirations

2824
01:51:38,120 --> 01:51:40,720
because many people default to, well, then, you know,

2825
01:51:40,720 --> 01:51:42,840
I'll just be disappointed because it's not going to work out.

2826
01:51:42,840 --> 01:51:44,920
I don't want to think about what I want

2827
01:51:44,920 --> 01:51:46,800
because then I'll just be more disappointed.

2828
01:51:46,800 --> 01:51:49,040
And that particular frame of mind was actually discussed

2829
01:51:49,040 --> 01:51:50,800
in the series with Dr. Conti.

2830
01:51:50,800 --> 01:51:54,240
And he convinced me, and he's the expert,

2831
01:51:54,240 --> 01:51:57,340
that the opposite is actually true.

2832
01:51:57,340 --> 01:51:59,600
When we are able to overcome some of our anxiety

2833
01:51:59,600 --> 01:52:01,840
and really think about in a dedicated way

2834
01:52:01,840 --> 01:52:04,200
what we would like to create for ourselves in our lives,

2835
01:52:04,200 --> 01:52:05,800
both present and future,

2836
01:52:05,800 --> 01:52:07,980
and keeping in mind our events of past

2837
01:52:07,980 --> 01:52:11,060
because we always carry that life narrative forward,

2838
01:52:11,060 --> 01:52:13,120
then we are in a far better place

2839
01:52:13,120 --> 01:52:15,340
to actualize those goals and aspirations.

2840
01:52:15,340 --> 01:52:17,720
And he explained a variety of reasons why that's the case

2841
01:52:17,720 --> 01:52:19,440
in his clinical observations

2842
01:52:19,440 --> 01:52:21,040
and some of the other observations

2843
01:52:21,040 --> 01:52:22,400
that really support that statement.

2844
01:52:22,400 --> 01:52:25,020
So I highly encourage you to think about embracing

2845
01:52:25,020 --> 01:52:26,060
a process of journaling.

2846
01:52:26,060 --> 01:52:27,720
Again, you don't have to do this every day.

2847
01:52:27,720 --> 01:52:29,280
The journaling and the dream analysis

2848
01:52:29,280 --> 01:52:30,660
take a little bit more time,

2849
01:52:30,660 --> 01:52:32,460
but they are oh so valuable

2850
01:52:32,460 --> 01:52:34,820
for better understanding oneself concept.

2851
01:52:34,820 --> 01:52:39,020
And they really thread forward into real everyday actions

2852
01:52:39,020 --> 01:52:42,100
that can positively enrich your mood and mental health.

2853
01:52:42,100 --> 01:52:44,300
Now, any description of science-based tools

2854
01:52:44,300 --> 01:52:46,620
for mood and mental health would be incomplete

2855
01:52:46,620 --> 01:52:50,380
without including some tools related to processing of traumas.

2856
01:52:50,380 --> 01:52:53,260
Now, the processing of traumas is something that,

2857
01:52:53,260 --> 01:52:56,900
especially in the case of major traumas or repeated traumas,

2858
01:52:56,900 --> 01:52:58,460
really should be carried out

2859
01:52:58,460 --> 01:53:01,620
in concert with a expert-trained clinician.

2860
01:53:01,620 --> 01:53:03,980
That is a psychologist or psychiatrist

2861
01:53:03,980 --> 01:53:07,780
who's trained in helping people work through traumas.

2862
01:53:07,780 --> 01:53:09,900
However, even if you're working with somebody

2863
01:53:09,900 --> 01:53:11,840
who's expert in processing trauma,

2864
01:53:11,840 --> 01:53:15,020
there are specific tools that you can use on your own

2865
01:53:15,020 --> 01:53:17,740
to accelerate that process.

2866
01:53:17,740 --> 01:53:19,540
And for people who are working through

2867
01:53:19,540 --> 01:53:21,980
what are sometimes called more minor traumas,

2868
01:53:21,980 --> 01:53:24,060
these are sometimes called big T, big traumas,

2869
01:53:24,060 --> 01:53:25,540
and little T, little traumas.

2870
01:53:25,540 --> 01:53:28,380
However, that nomenclature doesn't take into account

2871
01:53:28,380 --> 01:53:31,340
the fact that most of us can probably tell

2872
01:53:31,340 --> 01:53:34,300
what the big traumas are for ourselves and for others,

2873
01:53:34,300 --> 01:53:35,420
but sometimes it's hard to tell

2874
01:53:35,420 --> 01:53:37,140
whether or not those small traumas,

2875
01:53:37,140 --> 01:53:39,780
the little T traumas, actually are big T traumas.

2876
01:53:39,780 --> 01:53:41,900
So this is one of the major reasons

2877
01:53:41,900 --> 01:53:43,620
why working with a licensed professional

2878
01:53:43,620 --> 01:53:45,140
is really going to be advantageous

2879
01:53:45,140 --> 01:53:47,980
and in many cases necessary to work through trauma.

2880
01:53:47,980 --> 01:53:51,220
That said, the self-directed protocols

2881
01:53:51,220 --> 01:53:53,300
for working through trauma

2882
01:53:53,300 --> 01:53:56,220
have a lot to do with how we think about,

2883
01:53:56,220 --> 01:53:58,100
but more importantly at times,

2884
01:53:58,100 --> 01:54:00,340
how we talk about those traumas.

2885
01:54:00,340 --> 01:54:02,020
And Dr. Paul Conte talked about this,

2886
01:54:02,020 --> 01:54:04,220
not so much in the four episode series with us,

2887
01:54:04,220 --> 01:54:06,660
but in a particular podcast episode

2888
01:54:06,660 --> 01:54:08,780
that he did with Dr. Peter Attia,

2889
01:54:08,780 --> 01:54:10,460
who some of you are perhaps familiar with

2890
01:54:10,460 --> 01:54:12,820
for his incredible podcast, The Drive,

2891
01:54:12,820 --> 01:54:15,300
but also for his excellent book, Outlive,

2892
01:54:15,300 --> 01:54:18,860
which deals with health span and lifespan or longevity.

2893
01:54:18,860 --> 01:54:20,860
Now, in that particular conversation

2894
01:54:20,860 --> 01:54:23,340
with Dr. Conte and Dr. Attia,

2895
01:54:23,340 --> 01:54:26,780
Dr. Conte emphasized the fact that one of the ways

2896
01:54:26,780 --> 01:54:28,780
that we hold ourselves back

2897
01:54:28,860 --> 01:54:32,820
and indeed can exacerbate the negative consequences of trauma

2898
01:54:32,820 --> 01:54:35,700
are the ways in which we modify our language

2899
01:54:35,700 --> 01:54:37,420
to describe those traumas.

2900
01:54:37,420 --> 01:54:39,780
And what he said, which is so important,

2901
01:54:39,780 --> 01:54:43,300
is that oftentimes we don't allow ourselves

2902
01:54:43,300 --> 01:54:47,100
to use language that's as big as is necessary

2903
01:54:47,100 --> 01:54:50,300
to explain that trauma and the impact of that trauma

2904
01:54:50,300 --> 01:54:52,100
on us and on others.

2905
01:54:52,100 --> 01:54:56,500
In fact, many people start to relegate their language

2906
01:54:56,500 --> 01:54:59,100
to more passable in a given sentence

2907
01:54:59,100 --> 01:55:01,300
or passable in a given conversation.

2908
01:55:01,300 --> 01:55:04,260
Now, what we're not talking about here is the idea that,

2909
01:55:04,260 --> 01:55:07,020
okay, you know, screaming at somebody else about your trauma

2910
01:55:07,020 --> 01:55:08,940
or using a lot of four-letter words

2911
01:55:08,940 --> 01:55:10,340
is necessarily the best way

2912
01:55:10,340 --> 01:55:11,900
to process that trauma verbally.

2913
01:55:11,900 --> 01:55:14,820
However, we are talking about allowing oneself,

2914
01:55:14,820 --> 01:55:17,820
either in spoken form or in written form,

2915
01:55:17,820 --> 01:55:20,500
to really allow the magnitude of a given trauma

2916
01:55:20,500 --> 01:55:24,780
to be expressed with a fair degree of intensity

2917
01:55:24,780 --> 01:55:28,140
and language that can capture at least some

2918
01:55:28,140 --> 01:55:31,580
of what that trauma represented for us or for others.

2919
01:55:31,580 --> 01:55:33,660
Now, as Dr. Conte pointed out,

2920
01:55:33,660 --> 01:55:35,980
all too often we do the opposite.

2921
01:55:35,980 --> 01:55:38,860
What ends up happening is people will experience

2922
01:55:38,860 --> 01:55:41,260
some sort of trauma, either major or minor,

2923
01:55:41,260 --> 01:55:43,380
maybe single or repeated trauma,

2924
01:55:43,380 --> 01:55:46,540
and rather than being comfortable talking about it,

2925
01:55:46,540 --> 01:55:49,260
rather than using language that captures at least some

2926
01:55:49,260 --> 01:55:52,020
of the magnitude of that trauma for them,

2927
01:55:52,020 --> 01:55:56,220
people start to talk about that trauma less frequently.

2928
01:55:56,220 --> 01:55:58,460
They start to distract themselves

2929
01:55:58,460 --> 01:56:00,660
to think about other things instead of talking about

2930
01:56:00,660 --> 01:56:02,220
or thinking about that trauma.

2931
01:56:02,220 --> 01:56:04,860
And what happens is that trauma roots

2932
01:56:04,860 --> 01:56:06,420
into our unconscious mind

2933
01:56:06,420 --> 01:56:09,380
and starts to impact us in negative ways.

2934
01:56:09,380 --> 01:56:13,060
Now, those negative ways include increases in anxiety,

2935
01:56:13,060 --> 01:56:14,580
disruptions in sleep.

2936
01:56:14,580 --> 01:56:17,220
In fact, one of the common ways in which trauma manifests

2937
01:56:17,220 --> 01:56:19,500
in disruptions in sleep by way of rooting

2938
01:56:19,500 --> 01:56:23,660
into our unconscious is that people wake up at 2.30

2939
01:56:23,660 --> 01:56:25,300
or three o'clock in the morning,

2940
01:56:25,300 --> 01:56:27,660
let's just say after several hours of being asleep,

2941
01:56:27,660 --> 01:56:30,140
and immediately they're thinking about that thing

2942
01:56:30,140 --> 01:56:32,140
that happened and they're upset about it.

2943
01:56:32,140 --> 01:56:34,780
The idea is that when we push those traumas down,

2944
01:56:34,780 --> 01:56:37,780
when we don't talk about them with people that we trust,

2945
01:56:37,780 --> 01:56:39,980
when we don't have a way to consciously process

2946
01:56:39,980 --> 01:56:44,580
those traumas using language that at least partially matches

2947
01:56:44,580 --> 01:56:48,180
the magnitude of the impact of those traumas for us,

2948
01:56:48,180 --> 01:56:51,180
well, then those traumas impact our unconscious mind

2949
01:56:51,180 --> 01:56:53,260
in ways that lead our unconscious mind

2950
01:56:53,260 --> 01:56:55,340
to literally wake us up in the middle of the night

2951
01:56:55,340 --> 01:56:56,980
and remind us of that thing.

2952
01:56:56,980 --> 01:56:58,980
It's as if it's being thrown back in our face

2953
01:56:58,980 --> 01:56:59,900
over and over.

2954
01:56:59,900 --> 01:57:02,180
Also, sometimes traumas will root their way down

2955
01:57:02,180 --> 01:57:04,980
into our unconscious and then they will resurface

2956
01:57:04,980 --> 01:57:08,740
in the mode of compulsive or obsessive thinking

2957
01:57:08,740 --> 01:57:11,180
about that thing or perhaps other things.

2958
01:57:11,180 --> 01:57:14,700
Again, the unconscious mind has a interesting

2959
01:57:14,700 --> 01:57:16,820
and complicated number of different ways

2960
01:57:16,820 --> 01:57:21,820
that it defends us in ways that it can create denial,

2961
01:57:21,820 --> 01:57:24,580
distraction, that we might get hyper-focused on work

2962
01:57:24,580 --> 01:57:26,980
as a way to not think about the trauma

2963
01:57:26,980 --> 01:57:29,500
or hyper-focused on some details in our environment

2964
01:57:29,500 --> 01:57:30,980
and just really trying to focus on that

2965
01:57:30,980 --> 01:57:33,180
because it's much easier to process

2966
01:57:33,180 --> 01:57:35,220
and handle that than these traumas.

2967
01:57:35,220 --> 01:57:37,660
Again, the processing of trauma is a whole landscape

2968
01:57:37,660 --> 01:57:42,060
into itself that actually was beautifully described

2969
01:57:42,060 --> 01:57:44,660
in terms of how it arises within us

2970
01:57:44,660 --> 01:57:48,220
and how to process traumas in a really structured way

2971
01:57:48,220 --> 01:57:51,380
in a just fabulous book that was written by Dr. Conti

2972
01:57:51,380 --> 01:57:53,260
called The Invisible Epidemic,

2973
01:57:53,260 --> 01:57:55,660
How Trauma Works and How We Can Heal From It.

2974
01:57:55,660 --> 01:57:57,860
And in that book, Dr. Conti explains a number

2975
01:57:57,860 --> 01:58:00,340
of different ways that we can do self-directed work

2976
01:58:00,340 --> 01:58:02,540
as well as work with licensed professionals

2977
01:58:02,540 --> 01:58:05,100
to process traumas and help us move through those traumas

2978
01:58:05,100 --> 01:58:08,540
so that they are not negatively impacting us going forward.

2979
01:58:08,540 --> 01:58:11,060
So I really encourage anyone that's trying to process traumas

2980
01:58:11,060 --> 01:58:14,340
from the past and or present to check out Dr. Conti's book

2981
01:58:14,340 --> 01:58:16,300
because it's a spectacular resource.

2982
01:58:16,300 --> 01:58:18,700
But in terms of the tools related to processing trauma

2983
01:58:18,700 --> 01:58:20,620
that we're talking about right now,

2984
01:58:20,620 --> 01:58:24,100
I think this point about really making sure

2985
01:58:24,100 --> 01:58:27,620
that we allow ourselves to verbally process

2986
01:58:27,620 --> 01:58:29,740
and emotionally process that trauma

2987
01:58:29,740 --> 01:58:33,340
in a way that there's room for using language

2988
01:58:33,340 --> 01:58:35,940
that captures some of the magnitude of that trauma

2989
01:58:35,940 --> 01:58:38,460
and how it impacted us and others

2990
01:58:38,460 --> 01:58:40,340
is going to be very important

2991
01:58:40,340 --> 01:58:42,700
because otherwise what ends up happening

2992
01:58:42,700 --> 01:58:46,460
is that we tend to adopt feelings of guilt and shame

2993
01:58:46,460 --> 01:58:49,780
around those traumas simply by not talking about them,

2994
01:58:49,780 --> 01:58:51,140
by having them go inward.

2995
01:58:51,140 --> 01:58:53,540
And then they start to negatively impact

2996
01:58:53,540 --> 01:58:55,780
our unconscious mind and then our unconscious mind

2997
01:58:55,780 --> 01:58:57,260
tries to throw them up to the surface

2998
01:58:57,260 --> 01:58:58,900
for our conscious mind to recognize

2999
01:58:58,900 --> 01:59:00,740
by waking us up from sleep.

3000
01:59:00,740 --> 01:59:04,020
And in some cases, by leveraging those unhealthy defenses,

3001
01:59:04,020 --> 01:59:07,580
things like denial, things like the overindulgence

3002
01:59:07,580 --> 01:59:09,740
in alcohol, overindulgence of drugs,

3003
01:59:09,740 --> 01:59:11,580
ways to distract ourselves,

3004
01:59:11,580 --> 01:59:13,900
as well as projection and sublimation

3005
01:59:13,900 --> 01:59:16,020
and the other types of defenses

3006
01:59:16,020 --> 01:59:18,780
that Dr. Conti talked about in the four episode series.

3007
01:59:18,780 --> 01:59:22,620
Again, those defenses are not necessarily good or bad.

3008
01:59:22,620 --> 01:59:24,420
It depends on the circumstances.

3009
01:59:24,420 --> 01:59:27,180
The unconscious mind is not trying to harm us.

3010
01:59:27,180 --> 01:59:29,460
Your unconscious mind is part of you.

3011
01:59:29,460 --> 01:59:30,740
It is you.

3012
01:59:30,740 --> 01:59:33,140
But of course it is you acting in concert

3013
01:59:33,140 --> 01:59:34,260
with your conscious mind.

3014
01:59:34,260 --> 01:59:36,260
And so really the tools and protocols

3015
01:59:36,260 --> 01:59:38,740
from the four episode series with Dr. Conti

3016
01:59:38,780 --> 01:59:42,060
are aimed at helping you feel and access

3017
01:59:42,060 --> 01:59:45,260
more sense of agency and gratitude on a regular basis,

3018
01:59:45,260 --> 01:59:47,620
more peace, contentment and delight.

3019
01:59:47,620 --> 01:59:51,860
And doing so by touching into those different drives,

3020
01:59:51,860 --> 01:59:53,420
understanding what they are,

3021
01:59:53,420 --> 01:59:55,300
the aggressive drive, the pleasure drive,

3022
01:59:55,300 --> 01:59:58,060
and really making sure that your generative drive,

3023
01:59:58,060 --> 02:00:00,100
again, I love this description of the generative drive

3024
02:00:00,100 --> 02:00:01,660
so much so that I'm going to read it again,

3025
02:00:01,660 --> 02:00:05,500
because this is really what it means to be mentally healthy.

3026
02:00:05,500 --> 02:00:07,700
Again, the generative drive is our desire

3027
02:00:07,700 --> 02:00:09,660
to create, build and contribute to the world

3028
02:00:09,660 --> 02:00:12,780
in a meaningful way and appreciate the process to get there.

3029
02:00:12,780 --> 02:00:15,580
It is the core feature of our mental health.

3030
02:00:15,580 --> 02:00:17,940
So being able to access that generative drive

3031
02:00:17,940 --> 02:00:20,420
on a regular basis is really what this thing

3032
02:00:20,420 --> 02:00:23,020
that we call mental health is all about.

3033
02:00:23,020 --> 02:00:24,820
And the tools that I just described,

